INSERT INTO `jee` (`question`, `answer`) VALUES
('force', 'mass * acceleration'),
('formula of water', 'h20'),
('mansi', 'α\r\nβ'),
('x²', 'x²'),
('Consider two quadratic expressions f(x) = ax^2 + bx + c and g(x) = ax^2  + px + p, (a, b, c, p, q, ∈ R, b ≠ p) such that their discriminants are equal. If f(x) = g(x) has a root x = α, then what is α ?', 'aα^2 + bα + c = aα^2 + pα + q\r\n\r\n	α = [(q- c)/(b-p)]\r\n\r\nA.M. of roots of f(x) = 0 and g(x) = 0 is =  [(–b / a) –( p / a)]/4 =    -(b+p)/4a\r\n\r\nSince discriminants are equal :\r\nb^2 – 4ac = p2  – 4aq\r\nb^2  – p^2  = 4ac – 4aq\r\n\r\n(b+p)/4a = [(c-q) / (b-p)] =  -α\r\n\r\nso, \r\n                                         α  = A.M. of roots of f(x) = 0 and g(x) = 0\r\n'),
('If for all real values of a one root of the equation x2  – 3ax + f(a) = 0 is double of the other, then f(x) is equal to :', 'Let α,  2α are the roots of equation\r\nso α + 2α = 3α = 3a =  α = a\r\nand α(2α) = 2α^2  = f(a)\r\n = f(a) = 2a^2\r\nHence f(x) = 2x^2\r\n'),
('A quadratic equation, product of whose roots x1  and x2  is equal to 4 and satisfying the relation x1/(x1 - 1) + x2/(x2 - 1) = 2  is :', 'Since (x1)(x2) = 4\r\n\r\nx2 = x1/4\r\n\r\n(x1)/(x1- 1) + [(4/x1)/ (4/x1- 1)] = 2\r\n2(x1 -1)(4 - x1)\r\n\r\n=    x^2 - 2x =4 = 0'),
('A real values of a, for which sum of the roots of the equation x2  – 2ax + 2a – 1 = 0 is equal to the sum of the square of its roots, is :', ' α + 	β = 	α^2 + β^2\r\nα + β = [(α + β)^2] - 2αβ.\r\n\r\n2a = 4a^2 – 2 (2a – 1) \r\n\r\n2a^2 – 3a + 1 = 0\r\n\r\na = 1, 1/2.'),
('If  α, β are the roots of the roots of the quadratic equation x2  + px + q = 0 and 	γ, δ are the roots of x2  + px – r = 0 then (α - γ)(α - δ) is equal to ?', 'Since α,β are roots of the equatiion x^2+ px + q = 0\r\n\r\nα^2 + pα +q = 0,     α^2 + pα = -θ                 -----------------------(1)\r\n\r\nany γ, δ are roots of the equation x^2 + px – r = 0\r\n\r\nγ + δ = -p,     γδ = - r\r\n\r\n(α -γ)(α -δ) =  α^2 - (γ + δ)α + γδ              ------------------------(2)\r\n\r\nFrom 1 and 2 :\r\n  α^2 + pα + (-r) = -q-r =             -( q+r )    '),
('The value of the expression x^4  – 8x^3  + 18x^2  – 8x + 2 when x = 2 + √3 is :', 'x = 2 + √3    √3.\r\n[(x - 2)^2] = 3                                 x^2 – 4x + 1 = 0    -------------(1)\r\n[(x-2)^4] = 9                                 x^4 – 8x^3 + 24x^2 – 32x + 16 = 9     ---------------------(2)\r\n\r\nx^4 – 8x^3 + 18x^2 – 8x + 2 + 6(x2 – 4x + 1) – 1 = 0\r\n\r\nfrom (i) we get                                                x^4 – 8x^3 + 18x^2 – 8x + 2 = 1.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n'),
('The quadratic expression 21 + 12x – 4x2  is takes the greatest value as:', 'Since it is downward parabola, greatest value = – (D/4a)\r\n\r\n– [144 – 4(21)(–4) / 4(–4)]= 30 '),
(' If α,β are the roots of the equation ax^2  + bx + c = 0, then what are the the roots of the equation ax^2  – bx (x – 1) + c(x – 1)2  = 0 ', '[(ax^2)/ (1-x)^2] + [(bx)/(1-x)] + c = 0                              -----------------------(1)\r\n\r\nIf t = α, then t = x/(1-x),           α = x/(1-x)\r\n\r\nx = α/(α+1);\r\nroots are :  α/(1+α) , β/(1+β)'),
('If a > 2, roots of the equation (2 – a) x2  + 3ax – 1 = 0 are :', 'Let f(x) = x^2– 3ax/(a – 2)+ 1/(a – 2) = 0 ,                                                        a – 2 > 2\r\n\r\nD = [(9a^2)/(a-2)^2] - 4[1/ (a-2)]  = {8a^2 + [(a-2)^2] +4} >9\r\n\r\nf(0) = 1/(a-2) = 0\r\nand -b/2a =          3a/2(a-2) >0\r\n\r\nD > 0   also , -b/2a >0                                    ,so both the roots in th equation are positive'),
(' If the equations ax^2  + bx + c = 0 and 5x^2  + 12x + 13 = 0 have a common root, where a , b and c are the sides of a triangle ABC, then triangle ABC is :', 'Since equation 5x^2 + 12x + 13 = 0 has imaginary roots.\r\nHence equations  :  ax^2 + bx + c = 0 &  5x^2+ 12x + 13 = 0 have both common roots.\r\na/5 = b/12 = c/13 = k (say)\r\na = 5k, b = 12k, c = 13k\r\na^2 + b^2 = 25k^2 + 144k^2 = 169 k^2 = (13k)^2 = c^2\r\n\r\na2 + b2 = c2\r\n ABC is right angled triangle.'),
('If x + y + z = 5 and xy + yz + zx = 3, then least and largest value of x are :', 'xy + yz + zx = 3\r\n xy + y (5 – x – y) + (5 – x – y) x = 3 ( z = 5 – x – y)\r\n\r\nxy + 5y – xy – y2 + 5x – x2 – xy = 3\r\n x2+ y2+ xy – 5x – 5y + 3 = 0\r\n y2+ y (x – 5) + x2 – 5x + 3 = 0\r\n\r\nSince y is real, therefore, D ≥ 0,\r\n(x – 5)2 – 4.1. (x2 – 5x + 3)  ≥  0\r\n x2 – 10x + 25 – 4x2 + 20x – 12  ≥ 0\r\n – 3x2 + 10x + 13 ≤  0\r\n x (3x – 13) + 1 (3x – 13) ≤  0\r\n (x + 1) (3x – 13) ≤ 0'),
('Set of all values of x satisfying the inequality ( x^2 – 7x +6)^(1/2)  > x + 2 is', 'x^2 – 7x + 6 ≥ 0\r\nx ∈ (– ∞, 1] ∪ [6, ∞)\r\n\r\nCASE 1:\r\n[(x^2 - 7x + 6)]^(1/2) > (x +2);\r\nx ≤ -2,\r\n\r\nx ∈ (-∞, -2)\r\n\r\nCASE 2:    x ≤ -2,\r\n\r\nx2 – 7x + 6  ≥  x2 + 4x + 4\r\n\r\n– 11x > – 2,                 x < (2/11)\r\n\r\nx ∈ (-2, 2/11).   ,\r\nx ∈ (-∞, 2/11)\r\n\r\n\r\n'),
('If x1  and x2  are the arithmetic and harmonic mean of the roots of the equation ax2  + bx + c = 0, then quadratic equation whose roots are x1  and x2  is', 'α + β = -(b/a)\r\nαβ = (c/a)\r\n\r\nx1 = [(α + β)/2]                                                  x2 = [2αβ/(α +β)]    \r\n\r\nSo equation whose roots are x1 and x2 is :\r\n\r\nx^2 -x { [(α + β)/2] + [2αβ/(α +β)] } + αβ = 0\r\n\r\nx^2 + x {[(b^2) + 4ac]/2ab}  +  c/a  = 0.\r\n\r\n(2ab)x^2 + (b2 + 4ac) x + 2bc = 0 \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n'),
('The number of quadratic which are unchanged by squaring their roots, is :', 'αβ =  (αβ)^2                --------------------------(1)\r\n\r\nα + β = α^2 + β^2    -----------------------------(2)\r\n\r\nFrom (1)  αβ  = 0 or αβ  = 1\r\n\r\nCase 1 : If  αβ= 0 then we have following possibilities,\r\n\r\n(i) If α  = 0 then from (2)α = 0 or β = 1\r\n(ii) If β = 0 then from (2) α  = 0 or α  = 1\r\n\r\n from (i), and (ii) we can say that roots are  α = 0, β= 0 or α = 0, β = 1\r\nRequired quadratic equations are x^2 = 0 or x^2 – x = 0.\r\n\r\nCase 2 : If αβ = 1 then from (2) we get :\r\n\r\nα + β = α^2 + β^2 =  [[(α + β)^2] - 2αβ],                                αβ = 1\r\n\r\nα + β = -1, 2\r\n So the equations are :                         x^2 + x + 1 = 0   and  x^2 – 2x + 1 = 0 \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n'),
('If p, q, r, s, ∈ R, then equation (x^2  + px + 3q) (–x^2  + rx + q) (–x^2  + sx –2q) = 0 has :', 'Dis. of x^2 + px + 3p  is  p^2– 12p =  D1\r\nDis. of – x^2 + rx + q is r^2 + 4q    =   D2\r\nDis. of – x^2 + sx – 2q is s^2 – 8q  =  D3\r\n\r\nCase 1 : If q < 0, then D1 > 0, D3 > 0 and D2 may or may not be positive\r\nCase 2 : If q > 0, then D2 > 0 and D1, D3 may or may not be positive\r\nCase 3 : If q = 0, then D1 ≥ 0 , D2 ≥ 0, D3 ≥ 0.\r\n\r\nFrom Case 1, Case 2 and Case 3 we can say that the given equation has at least two real roots.\r\n\r\n'),
('If a, b, ∈ R and ax^2 + bx + 6 = 0, a ≠ 0 does not have two distinct real roots, then:', 'f(x) = ax2+ bx + 6 f(0) = 6 > 0\r\n a > 0\r\nfor x = 3   =                         a[(3)^2] + 3b + 6 ≥ 0  =                  3a + b ≥ – 2\r\nfor x = 6  =                    a[6^(2)]+ 6b + 6 ≥ 0         =                  6a + b ≥ – 1'),
('If the quadratic equation (ab – bc) x^2  + (bc – ca) x + ca – ab = 0, a, b, c ∈ R, has both the roots equal, then:', ' x = 1 is a root of the equation,  other root is also 1.\r\n(ca-ab)/(ab - bc) = 1\r\n\r\n2ab = bc + ac                   i.e.                              c = (2ab)/(a+b)\r\n\r\nso a,b,c are in HP\r\n\r\n[(b^2)(a^2)(c) -(a)(b^2)(c^2)] / [(a^2)(c^2)(b) - (b^2)(a^2)(c)]                    =                      (ab - bc) / (ac - ab)  = 1\r\n\r\na(b^2)(c^2), (b)(a^2)(c^2) and   (c)(b^2)(a^2)  are in AP.'),
('One real solution of the equation (x2  + 2) + 8x2  = 6x (x2  + 2) is', 'Let y = x^2 + 2\r\ny^2 + 8x^2 = 6xy\r\ny = 4x or 2x\r\nIf y = 4x, then x = 2 ± (2)^(1/2)\r\nIf y = 2x, then there is no real solution\r\nso x = 2 (2^(1/2)) , 2 – ((2)^(1/2))'),
('Statement-1 : The quadratic equation (a – b) x2  + (b – c)x + (c – a) = 0 have one root x = 1.  Statement-2 : If sum of the co-efficients in a quadratic equation vanishes then its one root is x = 1. Which of the following statement is true?', 'Statement 1 is true because :\r\n\r\na – b + b – c + c – a = 0\r\n If quadratic equation ax^2 + bx + c = 0 have one root x = 1 then a + b + c = 0\r\nsum of co-efficients = 0\r\n'),
('Statement-1 : The equation (x – p) (x – r) + λ (x – q) (x – s) = 0, p > q < r < s, has non real roots if λ > 0.  Statement-2 : The equation ax^2  + bx + c = 0, a, b, c, ∈ R, has one real roots if b2  – 4ac < 0.  Which of the following statement is true ?', 'Statement 2 is true because :\r\n\r\n\r\nStatement-1 : Let f(x) = (x – p) (x – r) + λ (x – q) (x – s),\r\nf(p) =  λ(p – q) (p – s), f(q) = (q – p) (q – r),                f(s) = (s – p) (s – r) and f(r) = λ (r – q) (r – s)\r\n\r\nIf λ > 0 then f(p) > 0, f(q) < 0, f(r) < 0 and f(s) > 0\r\n\r\nf(x) = 0 has one real root between p and q and other real root between r and s\r\nstatement-2 : Obviously true\r\n\r\n'),
('Statement-1 : If root of the equation x^2  – bx + c = 0 are two consecutive integers, then (b^2)  – 4ac = 1.   Statement-2 : If a, b, c are odd integer then the roots of the equation 4 ab(x^2)  + ((b^2)  – 4ac) x – b = 0 are real and distinct.  Which of the following statement is true ?', 'Statement-1 : Given equation x^2 – bx + c = 0.\r\nLet 	α, β two roots such that |α – β| = 1\r\n\r\n[(α + β)^2] – 4αβ = 1\r\n(b^2) – 4c = 1\r\n\r\n\r\nStatement-2 : Given equation 4abc (x^2)+ ((b^2)– 4ac) x – b = 0\r\nD = [((b^2) – 4ac)^2] + 16 a(b^2) c\r\n\r\nD = [((b^2) + 4ac)^2] > 0\r\nHence roots are real are unequal.\r\n\r\n'),
('Statement-1 : If one roots is (5^(1/2)) – (2^(1/2)) then the equation of lowest degree with rational coefficient is x^4  – 14x^2  + 9 = 0.  Statement-2 : For a polynomial equation with rational co-efficient irrational roots occurs in pairs. Which of the statement is true ?', ' Statement-1 is True, Statement-2 is True; Statement-2 is a correct a explanation for Statement1.\r\n\r\nx =  (5^(1/2)) – (2^(1/2))        squaring both side.\r\n(x^2) = 5 + 2 – 2 (10^(1/2))\r\n[((x^2) – 7)^2]= 40\r\n\r\nx^4 – 14x^2 + 49 = 40\r\n(x^4) – 14(x^2)+ 9 = 0\r\n\r\nFor polynomial equation with rational co-efficients irrational roots occurs in pairs.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n'),
('Statement-1 : The number of values of \'a\' for which [(a2  – 3a + 2) x^2]  + (a2  – 5a + 6) x + (a^2)  – 4 = 0 is an identity in x is 2.   Statement-2 : If a = b = c = 0, then equation a(x^2)  + bx + c = 0 is an identity in x. Which of the statement is true?  ', 'D) Statement-1 is False, Statement-2 is True because :\r\n\r\n\r\nStatement-1 : (a^2) – 3a + 2 = 0       =     a = 1, 2           \r\n\r\n (a^2) – 5a + 6 = 0                    =                      a = 2, 3,\r\n                \r\n(a^2)– 4 = 0                            =                               a = ± 2\r\na = 2 is the only solution. Hence statement 1 is false.\r\n\r\nStatement-2 : is true by definition.\r\n'),
('Elasticity', 'The properties of matter by virtue of which the body change its shape and size by applying the deforming force and after removing that force the regain its original shape and size is called elasticity.\r\n      Ex-  Rubber, Spring, etc.\r\n    That type of body which is follow the elasticity properties is called elastic body.\r\n'),
('Stress', 'The restoring force per unit area is called stress.\r\n                                               \r\n                                       Stress =   Restoring force / Area\r\n                                        Stress=    F / A\r\n'),
('Define types of stress.', 'Stress are three types.\r\n1-   Longitudinal stress-   \r\n2-   Shearing stress-       It is also called Tangential stress. \r\n3-   Volumetric stress-   It is also called Bulk stress or Hydraulic  stress.'),
('Strain', 'The ratio of the change in configuration to the body to the original      configuration is called strain.\r\nStrain = Change in configuration / Original configuration\r\nStrain has no unit and dimension.\r\n'),
('Types of strain.', 'Strain is three types:\r\n 1 -  Longitudinal strain –\r\n 2 -  Volumetric strain –\r\n3 -  Shearing strain – \r\n'),
('Stress-Strain Curve', 'The stress-strain relationship for materials is given by the material’s stress-strain curve. Under different loads, the stress and corresponding strain values are plotted. An example of a stress-strain curve is given below.\r\n'),
('Various points on the stress strain curve', 'Proportional limit\r\nElastic limit\r\nYield point\r\nUltimate stress point\r\nFracture or breaking point\r\n'),
('Hook’s law ', 'According to this law –\r\nWithin the elastic limit, stress is proportional to strain.\r\n                                         \r\n                                           E = Stress / Strain\r\n\r\n  where E is a constant which is known as modulus of elasticity of the material.\r\n   that’s law is valid only in the linear portion of the stress strain curve.\r\n  The modulus of elasticity depends on nature of the material of the body.\r\n         The modulus of elasticity of a body is independent of its dimension.\r\n'),
('Modulus of Elasticity ', 'Within the elastic limit it is the ratio of stress to strain.\r\n                              E= stress / strain\r\n Its  SI unit is Newton per square meter or Pascal\r\n'),
('Types of modulus of elasticity', 'There are three types of modulus of elasticity.\r\n 1- Young ‘s Modulus-\r\n 2- Bulk ‘s Modulus –\r\n 3- Modulus of Rigidity-\r\n'),
('Young’s Modulus-', 'Within the elastic limit , it is the ratio of longitudinal stress to the longitudinal strain is called  Young’s modulus of  the material of the wire.\r\nIt is represented by Y.\r\n\r\n\r\n                                 Y= Longitudinal stress/ Longitudinal strain \r\n \r\n\r\nLongitudinal stress= F/ A\r\n Longitudinal strain=  l/ L\r\n  Y= F/A/l/L\r\n Y= FL/Al\r\n  Y= m g L/ πr2 l\r\n'),
('Bulk’s Modulus', 'Within the elastic limit, it is the ratio of volumetric stress to the volumetric strain is called Bulk’s modulus.\r\n\r\nIt is represented by B.\r\n\r\n                              B= Volumetric stress/ Volumetric strain \r\n\r\n\r\n   B= F/A /v/V\r\n   B= FV/Av\r\n   B= - p V/ v\r\n'),
('Modulus of Rigidity-', 'Within the elastic limit, it is the ratio of shear stress to the shear strain. \r\nIt is represented by η\r\n                                    \r\n  η   = Shearing stress /Shearing strain\r\n                            η  =  F/A θ\r\n                          η   = FL / Al\r\nThe SI unit is shear modulus is Nm-2 or Pascal.\r\n'),
('Poisson’s Ratio', 'Within the elastic limit , it is the ratio of lateral strain to the longitudinal strain is called Poisson ‘s ratio.\r\nIt is represented by σ\r\n                                        \r\n                 σ = Lateral strain / Longitudinal strain\r\n \r\n                σ = - d/D / l L\r\n                 σ = - d L / D l\r\nThe negative sign indicates that longitudinal and lateral strain in opposite sense.\r\nIt has no unit and dimension.\r\nThe theoretical value of σ is -1 to 0.5 \r\nThe practical value of σ is 0to 0.5'),
('Elastic Potential Energy-', 'The work done in stretching the wire is stored in it as its elastic potential energy.\r\n     It is represented by U’\r\n            U = 1/2* F *l\r\n            U =1/2* F/A * l /L * AL\r\n           U = 1/2 * stress* strain* volume of wire\r\nElastic potential energy per unit volume of the wire or elastic energy density\r\n               μ   = ½  Young’s modulus * (Strain)2 \r\n                                       \r\n'),
('Energy Stored in a Deformed Body-', 'The work done in stretching the wire is stored in it as its elastic potential energy.\r\n     It is represented by U’\r\n            U = 1/2* F *l\r\n            U =1/2* F/A * l /L * AL\r\n           U = 1/2 * stress* strain* volume of wire\r\nElastic potential energy per unit volume of the wire or elastic energy density\r\n               μ   = ½  Young’s modulus * (Strain)2 \r\n                                       \r\n'),
('hg GH hmm', ''),
('what is math', ''),
('is at h', ''),
('Fluid', 'Fluid is a substance which began to flow when external force is applies on it. The study of fluid is known as hydrostatics or fluid static.\r\n'),
('Fluid pressure-', 'The thrust exerted by a fluid at rest per unit area of the surface in contact with it is called fluid pressure.\r\n                                                 P=F/A\r\n  The SI unit of pressure is Pascal,\r\n                                              1 Pascal=1Pa=1N/m2\r\n  One unit used principally in meteorology is the bar.\r\n1Bar=105pa or N/m2\r\n'),
('Atmospheric Pressure-', 'It is a pressure of the earth’s  atmosphere. Normal atmospheric pressure is  1.013*105pa or N/m2.\r\n\r\n'),
('Pressure exerted by a Liquid Column-', 'Consider  a fluid of density ρ is kept at rest; in a cylindrical vessel of height h then\r\n      Pressure applied by liquid at the bottom of the container is\r\n                    P=hρg \r\n  we can say that pressure applied by a liquid column is proportional to height of liquid    column.\r\n      If container is open the pressure P is\r\n                P= P0+hρg.\r\n\r\n'),
('Buoyancy-', 'Buoyancy is the force that that causes object to float. It is the force exerted on an object that is partly or whole     immersed in a fluid. Buoyancy is caused by the differences in pressure acting on opposite sides of an object immersed in a static fluid. It is also known as the buoyant force. Buoyancy is the phenomena due to Buoyant force.\r\n\r\nThe magnitude buoyant force depends on the cases\r\n (i) Density of the fluid\r\n (ii) Volume of object immersed in the liquid.\r\n\r\n'),
('Pascal’s Law-', 'Its law state that, the external pressure is applied on any part of a liquid contained in a vessel, it is transmitted undiminished and equally in all directions.\r\n\r\n'),
('Applications of Pascal law-', '	Hydraulic Lift-\r\nIt is used to lift heavy loads. It is a force multiplier\r\n\r\n Suppose a downward force f is applied on the smaller piston of cross-sectional area a then\r\nThe exerted Pressure by the piston:\r\n\r\n                      P= f/a\r\nSuppose Upward force on large piston is F\r\n\r\n                      F= p*A=                f / a *A =                    A/a *f\r\nUpward force on a piston,\r\n\r\n                       F = A f / a \r\n\r\nAs A>a, therefore F>f,\r\n\r\nThis show that the small forces applied on the smaller piston and very large force on a larger piston.\r\nDentists chair, car lift , jacks and hydraulic brakes are use this principle.\r\n\r\n'),
('Streamline Flow-', 'Streamline flow of a liquid is that in which each particle of the liquid passing through a point travels along the same path and with the same velocity as the proceeding particle passing through the same point.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n'),
('Properties of streamline-', 'Properties of streamline-\r\n   1.In streamline flow, no two stream lines can cross each other or no points intersect each other.\r\nThe greater is the crowding of streamline at a place greater of velocity of liquid particles at that place.\r\n\r\nLaminar flow-\r\n The liquid flows over a horizontal surface in the form of layers of different velocities, flow of liquid is called laminar flow. In this flow particles of one layer do not enter the another layer.\r\nEx- non viscous and viscous liquid in a pipe. \r\n\r\nTurbulent Flow-\r\n In turbulent flow the path and velocity of the particle of liquid change continuously and \r\nzig-zag haphazard flow of liquid.\r\n'),
('Properties of turbulent flow-', '1.The motion of liquid is irregular or disorder.\r\n2.All points crossing each other.\r\n'),
('Equation of Continuity –', 'It states that, during the streamline flow of the non- viscous and incompressible fluid through a pipe in varying cross-section , the product of area of cross-section and the fluid velocity remains constant through out the flow.\r\n\r\n    CONTINUITY EQUATION\r\n          a1 v1 = a2 v2\r\n       a v = constant\r\n'),
('Bernoulli’s Theorem-', ': Bernoulli’s Theorem-\r\n It state that, the sum of pressure energy per unit volume, kinetic energy per      unit volume and potential energy per unit volume of an incompressible, non-viscous fluid in a streamline flow remains constant at every cross-section throughout the liquid flow.\r\n\r\n p  +  ½ ρ (v^2)+ ρ g h = constant\r\n\r\nwhere    p is pressure energy per unit volume ½ ρ v2 is kinetic energy per unit volume\r\nρ g h   is potential energy per unit volume.\r\n\r\n'),
('Application of Bernoulli’s theorem –', 'Application of Bernoulli’s theorem –\r\n  1. Speed of Efflux- it is also called Torricelli’s theorem.\r\n  2.Venturimeter- It is also called flow meter or venture tube.\r\n  3.Blood flow and Heart Attack\r\n  4.Dynamic Lift\r\n\r\n'),
('Torricelli’s Theorem-', 'Torricelli’s Theorem-\r\n      According to this theorem, the velocity of efflux of a liquid issuing out of an orifice is the same as it would attain, if allowed to fall freely through the vertical height between the liquid surface and orifice.\r\n          The velocity of efflux:\r\n                  v =   2 g h\r\n'),
('Venturimeter', 'In the venturimeter the pressure difference in height h of two arms of U-tube is; \r\n               p1  -  p2 = ½ ρ (v^2) ρ[a1 / a2 -1]\r\n\r\nand velocity of fluid is;\r\n\r\n                v =   2 ρm g h / ρ [a1 / a2 -1]\r\n Volume of liquid flowing per second through the wider tube is;\r\n\r\nV = a1 a2   2 (p1  - p2 ) / ρ (a12 – a22).\r\n\r\n\r\n'),
('The flow of blood in a large artery of an anesthetised dog is diverted through a venturimeter. The wider part of the meter has a cross-sectional area equal to that of the artery A=16mm2. The narrower part has an area a= 8mm2 the pressure drop in the artery is 24 Pa. what is the speed of blood in the artery?', 'Sol: \r\n\r\n\r\nV = a1 a2   2 (p1  - p2 ) / ρ (a12 – a22).\r\n\r\nWhere A1 = 16mm^2\r\nA2 = 8mm^2\r\nρ = 1000 kg/m^3 or    1gm/cm^3\r\nP1 - P2 = 24Pa\r\n\r\nSo now, applying the above formula: \r\nV = (16)(8) * [2(24)]/ [1(256 - 64)]\r\n = 32mm.\r\n'),
('Viscosity', 'The property of fluid by virtue of which an internal force of friction comes in to play when the fluid is in motion and which opposes the relative motion between in different layers is called viscosity.\r\n\r\n In other words; fluids are no ideal and offer some resistance to motion. This resistance of fluid motion is like as internal friction to friction when a solid moves on a surface. It is called viscosity.\r\n\r\n   This force exist when there is relative motion between layers.\r\n'),
('Coefficient of Viscosity-', 'It is the ratio of shearing stress to the strain rate.\r\n          It is represented by η.\r\n                     η.= F l / A v\r\n   v / l = strain rate and F / A = shearing stress.\r\nThe SI unit of η is N s / m2 or Poiseuille.\r\n'),
('Effect of Temperature on the Viscosity- ', 'Viscosity of liquid decreases with increases in temperature\r\n                 η∝  1 / √T\r\n     viscosity of gases increases with increases in temperature                         \r\n                                    η∝ √T.\r\n\r\n'),
('Poiseiulle’s Law-', 'Poiseiulle’s Law-\r\nThe law of Poiseuille states that the flow of liquid depends on the following variables such as the length of the tube(L), radius (r), pressure gradient (∆P) and the viscosity of the fluid (η) in accordance with their relationship.\r\n      \r\n              The Poiseuille’s Law formula is given by:\r\n                                 Q = ΔPπr4 / 8ηl\r\nWhere in,\r\n  ΔP = pressure gradient\r\n    r = radius of tube\r\n   η = viscosity\r\n    l = length of tube\r\n \r\nResistance(R):\r\nThe resistance is calculated by 8Ln / πr4 and hence the Poiseuille’s law is\r\nQ= (ΔP) R\r\n \r\n'),
('Stokes Law-', ': According to this law – The backward force F, acting on a small spherical body of radius r, moving through a fluid of coefficient of viscosity η, with velocity v is given by \r\n                   F = 6 π η r v  \r\n'),
('Terminal Velocity-', 'Terminal velocity is defined as the highest velocity attained by an object that is falling through a fluid. It is observed when the sum of drag force and buoyancy is equal to the downward gravity force that is acting on the object. The acceleration of the object is zero as the net force acting on the object is zero.\r\nThe maximum constant velocity acquired by a body while falling through a viscous fluid is called terminal velocity.\r\n\r\n                                     v = 2/9 * r2 (ρ – σ) g / η\r\nwhere : \r\n\r\nρ = density of spherical body\r\nσ= density of fluid\r\n\r\n'),
('Critical velocity-', 'Critical velocity-\r\n \r\nThe limiting value of the velocity of flow up to which the flow streamline and above which the flow become turbulent is called critical velocity.\r\n The critical velocity vcof a liquid flowing through a tube depends on :\r\n\r\n(i)Coefficient of viscosity of the liquid (η)\r\n(ii)Density of liquid (ρ)\r\n(iii)Radius of tube r\r\n\r\n            Vc = k η/ ρr\r\n\r\n'),
('Reynold’s Number-', 'Reynold’s Number-\r\nReynolds number is a dimensionless quantity that is used to determine the type of flow pattern as laminar or turbulent while flowing through a pipe. Reynolds number is defined by the ratio of inertial forces to that of viscous force.\r\n\r\n                         Re = ρv D / η\r\n\r\nThe value of Reynold number lies 2000 to 3000.\r\nIf Re lies between 0 to 2000,flow of liquid streamline.\r\n \r\n \r\n  If Re is greater than 3000, flow of liquid is turbulent.\r\n  If Re lies between 2000 to 3000, the flow is unstable\r\n'),
('Surface Tension-', 'Surface Tension-\r\n         The property of liquid at rest by virtue of which free surface behaves likes a stretched membrane under tension and tries to occupy a small area as possible.\r\nSurface tension is measured as the force acting per unit length of imaginary line drawn on the free surface of liquid.\r\n    It is represented by T.\r\n\r\n                        T = F / L\r\n\r\nIts SI unit is N /m.\r\n It is scaler quantity.\r\nIt depends on temperature of liquid and medium of other side of liquid.\r\nSurface tension is zero at critical temperature.\r\nExamples- small drops, bubbles, hot soup, fresh food oil spread.\r\n\r\n'),
('Surface Energy- ', ': Surface Energy- \r\n\r\nThe amount of work done in increasing the area of the surface film through unity is called surface energy.\r\nIt is represented by E.\r\n\r\n E = W / a \r\n\r\nWhere a is change in area\r\n\r\nThe SI unit of surface energy is J/m2.\r\nThis work done is stored in the form of potential energy\r\n                   T = W / a\r\n\r\n'),
('Angle of Contact-', 'The angle which the tangent make to the free surface of the liquid at the point of contact with the walls of the vessel inside the liquid is called the angle of contact, or it is defined as the angle subtended between the tangents drawn at the liquid surface and the solid surface inside the liquid at the point of contact is called the angle of contact (θ).\r\n\r\nThe angle of contact depends upon the liquid’s nature and the solid in contact and the medium\r\n•	 and the medium which exists above the free surface of the liquid.\r\n•	The angle of contact increases with an increase in the temperature of the liquid.\r\n The angle of contact decreases on adding soluble impurity to a liquid.\r\n\r\n'),
('Importance of angle of contact-', 'The contact angle determines whether a liquid will spread on the surface of a solid or form droplets on it.\r\n\r\n•	If the Angle of contact is obtuse: then a droplet will be formed.\r\n•	If the Angle of contact is acute: then the water will spread.\r\n     \r\nThe curved surface of the liquid is called Meniscus.\r\n\r\n1- When the adhesive is more than the cohesive force, the shape of meniscus is concave. And angle of contact is less than 90 degree and wet solid.\r\n 2-When the adhesive force less than the cohesive force, the shape of meniscus is convex. And angle of contact is greater than 90 degree and liquid \r\n    does not wet the solid.\r\n3. The angle of contact is zero for pure water and clean glass and for alcohol and clean glass.\r\n\r\n'),
('Excess pressure inside a Soap bubble and Drop-', 'Excess pressure inside a Soap bubble and Drop-\r\n Surface tension is the causes of pressure difference between the inside and outside of a soap bubble or a liquid drop.\r\n 1- Excess pressure inside the soap bubble- \r\n\r\nSoap bubble consist of two spherical surface with a thin layer of liquid between them, the excess pressure is:\r\n\r\n                                                                       Δ p = 4T / R\r\nExcess pressure inside the liquid drop-\r\nA liquid drop has one surface film, the excess pressure is:\r\n\r\nΔ p = 2T / R\r\n'),
('Capillarity', 'Capillarity is a phenomenon of rise or fall of liquid surface relative to the adjacent general level of liquid. \r\nThis phenomenon is due to the combined effect of cohesion and adhesion of liquid particle.\r\n\r\n Formula of Capillary Rise-\r\n\r\n   When a capillary tube is dipped in a liquid then the level of liquid in capillary tube rises or fall with respect to free surface of liquid outside the capillary.\r\n\r\n\r\nThis phenomenon of rises or fall of liquid is called action.\r\n The formula of capillary motion is;\r\n\r\n               h = 2Tcos θ / r ρ g\r\n \r\n\r\n\r\n'),
('Factors of evaporation.', ':          Evaporation\r\nIt takes place at very much slower rate.\r\nIt can take place at any temperature.\r\nIt take place only from the surface of liquid.\r\nIts rate depends on many facotrs like temperature, humidity, surface area, speed of wind. \r\n'),
('Factors of boiling: ', 'Boiling\r\nIt occurs at much higher rate.\r\nIt take place always at fix temperature.\r\nIt takes place from all parts of liquids.\r\nIts rate does not depends at any such factors.\r\nIts rate depends on atmospheric pressure.\r\n\r\n'),
('Difference between Evaporation and Boiling.', 'Evaporation\r\nIt takes place at very much slower rate.\r\nIt can take place at any temperature.\r\nIt take place only from the surface of liquid.\r\nIts rate depends on many facotrs like temperature, humidity, surface area, speed of wind. \r\n\r\n                   Boiling\r\nIt occures at much higher rate.\r\nIt take place always at fix temperature.\r\nIt takes place from all parts of liquids.\r\nIts rate does not depends at any such factors.\r\nIts rate depends on atmospheric pressure.\r\n\r\n\r\n'),
('DRY ICE', 'Carbon dioxide which normally exist as a gas.\r\n	By compressing it to a very high pressure ( approx. 57 times that of normal atmospheric pressure ) it turns to liquid.\r\n	Many food venders use dry ice to keep food cool and frozen.\r\n	Solid CO2 is known as dry ice because it directly convert into gaseous form.\r\n\r\n'),
('INTERMOLECULAR FORCE', ': The force of attraction present between particles of matter is known as intermolecular force.\r\n	The force present between two similar types of particles is called cohesive force.\r\n	The force present between two different types of particles is called adhesive force.\r\n\r\n'),
('Interesting points about temperature and heat.', '1 g of potassium permanaganate can colour 10 9 litre of water.\r\n	The small quantity of air contains more air particals than grains of sand on a large beach.\r\n	You can not melt a paper to obtain a liquid .if you raise the temperature it chars instead of melting.\r\n	 The zig-zag movement of particals is known as Brownian motion.\r\n	Do not confuse with temperature with heat. Heat is the form of energy while temperature tells the quantity of heat present in any body.\r\n	A vapour can be liquified just by incresing the pressure.\r\n	A gas can be liqufied by lowering the temperature below its crtical temperature.\r\n	Condensation play important role in formation of rain,snow,frost,fog and dew.\r\n'),
('Critical Temperature and absolute zero.', 'The temperature at which a gas liquifies is called critical temperature . It is different for different gases.\r\n	 The lowest possible temperature for any gas is called absolute zero.\r\n	The temperature -273.15o C is given the value of absolute zero.\r\n	The critical temperature of helium gas close to absolute zero that is -268oC.\r\n\r\n'),
('Atmospheric temperature:', 'The temperature remain constant in thermometer when ice melts to form water and water boils to convert into steam.\r\n	This is because heat is used as latent heat to overcome the force of attraction which holds the particals together.\r\n	At sea level the atmospheric pressure is taken as 1 atmosphere and considered as normal atmospheric pressure. \r\n'),
('Two more states of matter:', 'Scientist have discovered two more states.\r\n. Plasma : which is a mixture of electrons and ions. Sun and stars glow due to plasma .  Artificially plasma can be created by passing a high voltage current through fluorescent tubes.\r\n. Bose-Einstein condensate : Which created at very low temp. called super low temperature. This is also called as supercooled atom.\r\n'),
('Elements and mixture facts:', '20 carat gold is the mixture of 20 parts by weight of gold and 4 parts by weight of copper.\r\n	Iodized salt used as a table salt is a mixture of Nacl and small amount of NaI.\r\n	The existance of a compound in different crytalline forms is called polymorphism and the different forms are called polymorphs. E.g ZnS has two polymorphs called zinc blende and wurtzite.\r\n\r\n'),
('What is “Solid state” of matter.', 'A substance is said to be solid if its melting point is above the room temperature under atmospheric pressure a solid substance always posses following characteristic:\r\n\r\n•Posses rigidity.               \r\n •They have high density\r\n•They posses definite shape and volume.\r\n•Their intermolecular distance is very less.\r\n•They are incompressible.\r\n\r\n'),
('Types of solids:', 'Solid can be classified into two categories.\r\n\r\n•Crystalline solid : Such solid in which the constituent particles i.e. atoms, ions, molecules have a regular arrangement throughout. Thus called long range order solid.\r\n\r\n•Atmosphere solid: Such solid in which the constituent particles do not posses regular arrangement. Thus they have irregular shape and known as short range order solid.-Atmosphere solid are also known as super cooled liquids because they posses some characteristics of liquids. e.g A glass became soft on heating and behave like a fluid.\r\n\r\n'),
('Why does the window glass of old buildings looks milky?', 'Due to continues healing in the day and cooling at night glass acquise some  crystalline characteristics that is called annealing of glass. That is why window glass of old buildings looks milky.\r\n\r\n'),
('What are crystalline solids ?', 'Crystalline solid\r\n•Thus are long range order solid and have regular geometry .\r\n•They have high melting and boiling point.\r\n•These solid give a sharp edge on cut with knife.\r\n•These solids are anisotropic in nature that means their properties like electrical conductivity, thermal conductivity, refractive index have different value in direction.\r\n\r\n\r\n'),
('What are amorphous Solids.', ':                  Amorphous solid\r\n•These are short range order.\r\n•They have  very less melting point.\r\n•They give a rough- surface on cut.\r\n•These solids are isotropic in nature that means they posses all properties like electrical conductivity, thermal conductivity refractive index, same in all directions.\r\n'),
('Difference btw Crystalline and Amorphous solids .', ':        Crystalline solid\r\n•Thus are long range order  solid and have regular geometry .\r\n•They have high melting and  boiling point.\r\n•These solid give a sharp edge on  cut with knife.\r\n•These solids are anisotropic in nature that means their properties like  electrical conductivity, thermal conductivity, refractive index have different value in direction.\r\n\r\n\r\n                  Amorphous solid: \r\n\r\n•These are short range order.\r\n•They have  very less melting point.\r\n•They give a rough- surface on cut.\r\n•These solids are isotropic in nature\r\n that means they posses all properties like electrical conductivity, thermal conductivity refractive index, same in all directions.\r\n-Actually crystalline solids are considered as true solid and Amorphous solid are considered as pseudo solids.\r\n\r\n'),
('Classification of crystalline solids:- ', 'Based on the interionic force between the particles crystalline solid are classified into four categories:-\r\n•Iconic Solid: Such solid in which the constituent particles are ions that means cations and anions eg:  NaCl,  kCl,  AgCl are crystalline ionic solid. Thus in ionic solid a strong electrostatic force is present between the ions. As a result.\r\n-They have high melting and boiling point.\r\n-They are electrical insulator in solid state but in aqueous condition or molten state they act as good conductors.\r\n-They are soluble in polar solvents like water.\r\n-Due to strong electrostatic force these solid are hard in nature.\r\n'),
('Molecular solid', 'Molecular solid: Such solid in which constituents particles are molecules. But depending upon the nature of bond these further are of two types.\r\n\r\n\r\n12.	Non - Polar molecular solid\r\nAns : :- Such solids in which the particles are \r\neither non polar molecules like H2,N2,O2,CI2 etc or atoms like noble gases \r\nlike helium, neon etc. Between these constituents particles a weak dispersion force is present. As a result:-\r\n-These solids are generally soft in nature.\r\n-These solids are non-conductor of electricity.\r\n-They have low melting and boiling point .\r\n-Due to weak force they are usually liquids or gases at room temp.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n13.	Polar Molecular solid:\r\nAns : Such solids in which polar bond is present between the constituent particles e.g : H2O, HCl etc. Between these constituent particles the force is comparatively stronger than weak dispersion force.\r\n\r\n'),
('Non - Polar molecular solid', 'Such solids in which the particles are \r\neither non polar molecules like H2,N2,O2,CI2 etc or atoms like noble gases \r\nlike helium, neon etc. Between these constituents particles a weak dispersion force is present. As a result:-\r\n-These solids are generally soft in nature.\r\n-These solids are non-conductor of electricity.\r\n-They have low melting and boiling point .\r\n-Due to weak force they are usually liquids or gases at room temp.\r\n\r\n'),
('Polar Molecular solid:', 'Such solids in which polar bond is present between the constituent particles e.g : H2O, HCl etc. Between these constituent particles the force is comparatively stronger than weak dispersion force.'),
('Hydrogen- bonded molecular solids', 'Such solids in which hydrogen bonding exist between the constituent particles e.g H2O, NH3.Thus, the intermolecular force is strong hydrogen bond between the molecules. Thus these solids.-exist as volatile liquids or soft solid at room temp.-Non conductor of electricity.-Their melting point is generally hard than above two type.\r\n\r\n\r\n'),
('Covalent solid', ' Covalent solid: Such solids in which constituent particles are non- metals and they linked to adjacent atoms by covalent bond. In such solid a large network of covalent bonds e.g Diamond and Graphite is the best example of covalent solids.\r\n-Since there exist in giant molecule so there solid are hard as well as brittle.\r\n-They have high melting and boiling point.\r\n-Since there is no ions hence there solids are poor conductor of electricity.\r\n-Exceptionally Graphite is good conductor of electricity.\r\n\r\n\r\n'),
('Metallic solids', 'Metallic solids: Such solids which made up of only one type of atoms. Generally all metals are solid. In metallic solid atoms are linked by metallic bond.\r\n-Exception mercury and gallium are metals in liquid form.\r\n-Metallic solid are electrical conductor in solid state due to the movement of electrons.\r\n-Metallic solid have high melting and boiling point since a large number of kernels and valence electrons are closely packed.\r\n-Metallic solids have high tensile strength.\r\n\r\n\r\n'),
('What are physical quantities?', 'All such quantities which we come across during our scientific studies are called Physical quantities.\r\n-The measurement of any physical quantity consist of two parts.\r\ni)Number     ii) The unit\r\neg:  The weight of an object is 5kg. It involves two parts 5 is the number and kg is the unit.\r\n\r\n\r\n'),
('What are SI units?', ': Here we are going to understand the concept of : significant figure Precision and accuracy, S.I units, unit measurements etc.\r\n•S.I. Units:- A unit is defined as the standard of reference chosen to measure any Physical quantity.-In easily times different type of units of measurement were popular in different parts of world e.g ser, pound, miles, yard. But these units were have lot of contradiction because these was no uniformity in conversion factor.\r\n\r\n'),
('How did SI units came into use ?', 'So to overcome the difficulties French Academy of Science in 1991. Introduced the new system called  Metri system.\r\n-In metric system different units of physical quantities are related to each other as multiples of power of 10.\r\ne.g 1km=10³m,1m=100cm.     , 1cm=10-²m etc.\r\n-India started following metric system since 195%\r\n-The metric system further improved in 1960 in France.\r\n-The improved system is called international system of units.\r\n\r\n'),
('Measurement of some physical  quantities:-', 'Measurement of some physical quantities:-\r\n\r\n\r\n1•Volume: volume has the unit (length)³.Thus the S.I unit of volume m³.But in laboratory generally smaller volumes are used . There for unit of volume is expressed in cm³.\r\n\r\n\r\n2•Mass:Mass is the quantity of matter contained in the sample for given sample it is constant. It does not depend upon the place. Where as weight is the force with which the body is attracted towards the earth.\r\n                                             W=mg\r\n\r\n\r\n5.	Temperature\r\nAns : Temperature: It is the feeling of hotness or coldness. Or we can say measurement of hotness and coldness. Temp. is generally measurement on three scales.\r\n1.°C degree celcius\r\n2.°F degree Fahrenheit\r\n3. K kelvin SI UNIT\r\n K=°C + 273.15 = °C + 273°F =9/5(°C) + 32\r\n\r\n\r\n'),
('On a particular day the temp. recorded in New York was 60°F. What would be the equivalent temp. in °C?', 'C= 5/9(°F-32)  =5/9(60-32)  = 5×28/9  =15.55  =15.6°'),
('UNIT Conversation Method', 'We can convert one type of Physical quantity given in one type of units into some other units \r\n•The method used is called unit factor method. Which involve the following step.\r\n1.First determine the unit conversion factor e.g conversation of inches into cm or vice-versa.1inch=2.54cm \r\n  .\r\n . . 1=2.54cm/1inch or 1 = 1inch/2.54cm2.\r\nMultiply the given physical quantity with unit conversion factor in such a way that all units cancel out leaving behind only the required units .\r\n3.If the conversion involves a number of steps each conversion factor is used in such a way that units of the preceding factors cancel out.\r\n\r\n\r\n'),
('At what temperature will both celcius and Fahrenheit scatles read the same value?', 'Suppose x is the temp. When both celsius scale and  fahrenheit scale read the same value. Then:-\r\n°F= 9/5(°C)+32   \r\n .\r\n. .  9/5(x)+32X-32 = 9/5(x)  5x=9x+32 -4×=150\r\n      x=-40°\r\n\r\n'),
('If you land in USA and temperature is 59°F, what do you expect cold or hot? ', 'C=5/9(°F-32)  =5/9(59-32)   =5/9(27)   =5×3=15°C\r\nUSA will be cold as compare to India.\r\n\r\n'),
('Why the temperature must also be mentioned while reporting a density?', 'When heated or cooled, the volume of substance increases or decreases. As density is mass divided by volume so density of a substance depends upon temperature'),
('Convert 39°c the human body temperature in Fahrenheit scale', ': °F = 9/5(37)+32   = 66.6+32=98.6°F\r\n\r\n'),
('Some important Term about Physical Quantities:-', ': Accurate Value: It means closeness of single measurement to its true value or in other word we can say \"if the average value of different measurement is close to the correct value the measurement is said to be accurate.\r\n\r\n-Precision: if the values of different measurements are close to each other the measurement is said to be precise.\r\n\r\nSignificant figures: the total number of digits in a number including the last digit whose value is inserting is called the number of significant figures.\r\ne.g suppose the mass of an object has been determined to be 14.5678g. If the accuracy of the analytical balance is 0.0001g that means the actual mass of the object may be 49.5678+_0.0001 it lies between 14.5677 and 14.5 679. Hence in this example first five digits are certain and last digit is uncertain.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n'),
('What are significant digits?', 'Significant figures: the total number of digits in a number including the last digit whose value is inserting is called the number of significant figures.\r\ne.g suppose the mass of an object has been determined to be 14.5678g. If the accuracy of the analytical balance is 0.0001g that means the actual mass of the object may be 49.5678+_0.0001 it lies between 14.5677 and 14.5 679. Hence in this example first five digits are certain and last digit is uncertain.\r\n .\r\n. . These are some rules of determining the number of significant figure.\r\n•All non zero digit Sa signification i.e 1-9\r\n•Zero between non-zero digits are always significant e.g 2.054 has u significant figures.\r\n• if zero is present at leading place mean left side to the non-zero digits are not significant e.g 0.0045 has only two significant fig.\r\n\r\n\r\n'),
('Scientific notation', 'It is the way to represent of very small and very large numbers in scientific manner that means in the form of N×10n is the exponent which may be positive or negative.\r\nAvogadro Numbers has a very large value that is 602,213,6700000000000 so it can be written as 6.022+10²³ that mean we shifted left side with 23 places.\r\n\r\n'),
('Organisms and populations', 'Ecology:- (oaks - homes; logos-study)\r\n\r\n	Ernst Hackle coined the term ecology.\r\n	Humboldt \" father of ecology \".\r\n	It is a branch of science that deals with the  inter- relationship among organisms and interaction between organisms and their environment. \r\n	Sub-division of ecology are:-\r\n	(a) Autecology/ species Ecology:- study of individual species in relation to the environment.  It includes study of life history,  behaviour,  \r\n            morphological features,  population, taxonomic positions , reproduction.\r\n	(b) Synecology/Ecosystem ecology:- study of group of organisms or population interacting among themselves or with the environment.  It \r\n               includes group of interbreeding species,  various kinds of competition,  predation,  how to conserve species, more complex than \r\n               autecology.  \r\n '),
('Organisms and populations', 'Ecology:- (oaks - homes; logos-study)\r\n\r\n	Ernst Hackle coined the term ecology.\r\n	Humboldt \" father of ecology \".\r\n	It is a branch of science that deals with the  inter- relationship among organisms and interaction between organisms and their environment. \r\n	Sub-division of ecology are:-\r\n	(a) Autecology/ species Ecology:- study of individual species in relation to the environment.  It includes study of life history,  behaviour,  \r\n            morphological features,  population, taxonomic positions , reproduction.\r\n	(b) Synecology/Ecosystem ecology:- study of group of organisms or population interacting among themselves or with the environment.  It \r\n               includes group of interbreeding species,  various kinds of competition,  predation,  how to conserve species, more complex than \r\n               autecology.  \r\n ');
