INSERT INTO `neet` (`question`, `answer`) VALUES
('features of Phylum Ctenophora', 'General Features:-\r\n\r\n1. Habitat: Marine feed on plankton, swimming (cilia),Bioluminescence (Property of emitting light).\r\n2. Body form: Variable, tentacles (may or may not be present).If present two in number.\r\n3. Symmetry: Radial symmetry (Comb plates); Bilateral symmetry(Tentacles and Branching)\r\n4. Level of organization: Tissue level of organization and Acoelomates\r\n5. Germ layer: Diploblastic animals.\r\n6. Body Wall: Epidermis(outer), Gastrodermis( Inner), Mesaglo,(Middle aslo called Collanchyma) Collablasts (Lasso cells) in epidermis of tentacles \r\n    of capture food.\r\n7. Locomotion: Comb like right ciliary plates- comb plates helps in swimming so, called comb jellies.\r\n8. Digestive system: Also called Gastrovascular tract include, mouth, pharynx, stomodacum, stomach or Infundibulum, anal canals, two and \r\n    pores.Complete digestive system. Digestion can be Extra or Intracellular (food vacuole)\r\n9. Absence of skeletal, circulatory, Respiratory and Excretory system\r\n10. Nervous system: statocyst present at aboral end.\r\n11. Reproduction:Hermaphrodite (Bisexual or Monecious);Asexual reproduction absent; Fertilization external;Paedogenesis is common \r\n     (Paedogenesis-larva reproduce another larva).'),
('features of Phylum Platyhelminthes', 'General Features:-\r\n1.Habitat: Parasites (with hooks and suckers) ,free-living  (Marine, freshwater, Terrestrial)\r\n2.Body form: Dorso-ventrally flattened, no true segments.\r\n3.Symmetry and level of organization: Bilateral symmetry and organ-system level of organization.\r\n4.Germ layer: Tripoblastic and Acoelomates animals\r\n5.Body wall: Body soft, with or without cilia.\r\n   Rhabdites(Rod-shaped cells) in epidermal cells to capture food. \r\n   Parenchyma( Space fill between body wall and organs) that help in transpiration of food material and also help in maintaining body shape (Hydro \r\n    skeleton)\r\n6. Absence of skeletal system, Respiratory system, Circulatory system.\r\n7. Excretory system: Flame cells (Solenocytes or Protonephridia) helps in \r\n    excretion, Ammonia(Excretory waste)\r\n8.  Digestive system: Incomplete.\r\n9.  Nervous system: ladder like nervous system include two logitudinal nerve cord connected by transverse commissures at several intervals.\r\n10. Reproduction: Hermaphrodite; fertilization (Internal); Asexual  reproduction by Binary fission. Development through larval stages i.e. Miracidium, sporocyst, Redia, Cercaria, Metercarcaria larva.'),
('features of Phylum Aschelminths/Nemathelminths (Round worms)', 'General Features:-\r\n1. Habitat: Parasites Plants and Animals, causes agriculture veterinary and health problems. Free living\r\n2. Body form: Unsegmented, cylindrical tapering at both ends.\r\n3. Body wall and cavity: Consists of non-living cuticile, syncytial epidermis(Multi nucleated cytoplasm), Muscle layer present,cilia absent. \r\n    Pseducoelom present filled with Pseducoelmic fluid.\r\n4. Germ layer: Triploblastic\r\n5. Symmetry and level of organization: Bulateral symmetry and organ-system level of organization.\r\n6. Skeleton: High fluid pressure in the pseudocoelon maintaince body shape (Hydroskeleton).\r\n7. Digestive tract: Complete type; with & muscular  pharynx and non- mascular intestine..\r\n8. Respiratory and circulatory system: Respiration through body surface by diffusion and circulatory system absent.\r\n9. Nervous system and sense organs: Have circumpharyngeal ring that give rise to nerves forward as well as backward.\r\n   (a)   Sense organs:-INSERT INTO `neet` (`question`, `answer`) VALUES
('VIRUSES', '1. Acellular organisms and hence not included under any of the five kingdoms. \r\n2. They are inert outside a host living cell and can replicate only using the machinery of the host cell they infected. Thus, obligate parasites.\r\n3. Dmitri Ivanowsky in 1892 observed that certain microbes tinier than bacteria were causing tobacco mosaic disease and named them as Virus.\r\n4. In 1898, M.W.Beijernick  observed that extract from infected plants could infect healthy plants and named the extract as Contagium vivium \r\n    fluidum.\r\n5.  In 1935, W.M.Stanley crystallized the viruses and observed that the crystals are mainly composed of proteins. \r\n6.  Viruses have outer protein shell or coat and inner genetic material that is either single-stranded or double-stranded DNA or RNA. Hence, they are \r\n     nucleoproteins where genetic material is infectious. \r\n7. Plant viruses usually have ssRNA and animal viruses have ssRNA or ds RNA or dsDNA. Bacteriophages have ds DNA. Certain animal viruses \r\n      like Parvovirus and plant viruses like Yellow leaf curl virus have ssDNA.\r\n8.The protein coat called Capsid is made of capsomere sub-units arranged in helical or polyhedral geometric forms and enclosed in the capsid is the \r\n     genetic material. Few viruses have an additional membrane called viral envelope around capsid. \r\n9.  They cause diseases like AIDS, COVID, Flu, Mumps etc in animals and yellowing, leaf curling, dwarfing, vein clearing in plants. \r\n      Infectious form of virus is VIRION.\r\n\r\nVIRIODS:\r\n1. In 1971, T.O.Diener discovered virions, infectious agents tinier than viruses in potato plants with spindle fibre disease. \r\n2. It was free RNA and no protein capsid was found. \r\n3. Single-stranded circular infectious RNA inhabitants of angiosperms.\r\n \r\nPRIONS:\r\n1. Infectious abnormally folded or misfolded protein agents.\r\n2. Similar in size to virus. Causes neurodegenerative diseases.\r\n3. Examples: Bovine Spongiform Encephalopathy in cattle and Creutzfeldt-Jacob disease in humans.\r\n \r\nLICHENS:\r\n1. Symbiotic associations between algae (phycobiont) and fungi (mycobiont).\r\n2. Phycobionts are autotrophic and mycobionts are heterotrophic.\r\n3. Do not grow in polluted areas. Hence, pollutant indicators. \r\n4. Fungi absorbs water and nutrients whereas algae prepares food. \r\n \r\n'),
('What do you mean by \"VIRUSES\" KINGDOM ?', '1. Acellular organisms and hence not included under any of the five kingdoms. \r\n2. They are inert outside a host living cell and can replicate only using the machinery of the host cell they infected. Thus, obligate parasites.\r\n3. Dmitri Ivanowsky in 1892 observed that certain microbes tinier than bacteria were causing tobacco mosaic disease and named them as Virus.\r\n4. In 1898, M.W.Beijernick  observed that extract from infected plants could infect healthy plants and named the extract as Contagium vivium \r\n    fluidum.\r\n5.  In 1935, W.M.Stanley crystallized the viruses and observed that the crystals are mainly composed of proteins. \r\n6.  Viruses have outer protein shell or coat and inner genetic material that is either single-stranded or double-stranded DNA or RNA. Hence, they are \r\n     nucleoproteins where genetic material is infectious. \r\n7. Plant viruses usually have ssRNA and animal viruses have ssRNA or ds RNA or dsDNA. Bacteriophages have ds DNA. Certain animal viruses \r\n      like Parvovirus and plant viruses like Yellow leaf curl virus have ssDNA.\r\n8.The protein coat called Capsid is made of capsomere sub-units arranged in helical or polyhedral geometric forms and enclosed in the capsid is the \r\n     genetic material. Few viruses have an additional membrane called viral envelope around capsid. \r\n9.  They cause diseases like AIDS, COVID, Flu, Mumps etc in animals and yellowing, leaf curling, dwarfing, vein clearing in plants. \r\n      Infectious form of virus is VIRION.\r\n\r\nVIRIODS:\r\n1. In 1971, T.O.Diener discovered virions, infectious agents tinier than viruses in potato plants with spindle fibre disease. \r\n2. It was free RNA and no protein capsid was found. \r\n3. Single-stranded circular infectious RNA inhabitants of angiosperms.\r\n \r\nPRIONS:\r\n1. Infectious abnormally folded or misfolded protein agents.\r\n2. Similar in size to virus. Causes neurodegenerative diseases.\r\n3. Examples: Bovine Spongiform Encephalopathy in cattle and Creutzfeldt-Jacob disease in humans.\r\n \r\nLICHENS:\r\n1. Symbiotic associations between algae (phycobiont) and fungi (mycobiont).\r\n2. Phycobionts are autotrophic and mycobionts are heterotrophic.\r\n3. Do not grow in polluted areas. Hence, pollutant indicators. \r\n4. Fungi absorbs water and nutrients whereas algae prepares food. \r\n \r\n'),
('Process of Sexual Reproduction in FUNGI.', '1. Occurs between two compatible mating types either homothallic (in same mycelia) or heterothallic (different but compatible mycelia) Occurs in \r\n     three stages. \r\n2. Compatible haploid hyphae fuse together = Anastomosis. The protoplasm of the hyphae fuse together = Plasmogamy.\r\n3. In certain classes of fungi, the nuclei fuse immediately (karyogamy) after anastomosis or plasmogamy to form a diploid cell.\r\n4. However, in fungi like Ascomycetes and Basidiomycetes the nuclei do not fuse immediately but exist in dikaryophase as dikaryon i.e., two nuclei \r\n     from two protoplasm, cohabit but does not fuse.  \r\n5. Later karyogamy occurs resulting in diploid cells.  \r\n6.Meiosis of diploid cells to form haploid spores occurs in the fruiting body of the fungi (Ascospores/Basidiospores).\r\n7. These spores can be dispersed and can germinate into new mycelium.\r\n \r\n'),
('Explain the process of Sexual Reproduction in \"FUNGI\"', '1. Occurs between two compatible mating types either homothallic (in same mycelia) or heterothallic (different but compatible mycelia) Occurs in \r\n     three stages. \r\n2. Compatible haploid hyphae fuse together = Anastomosis. The protoplasm of the hyphae fuse together = Plasmogamy.\r\n3. In certain classes of fungi, the nuclei fuse immediately (karyogamy) after anastomosis or plasmogamy to form a diploid cell.\r\n4. However, in fungi like Ascomycetes and Basidiomycetes the nuclei do not fuse immediately but exist in dikaryophase as dikaryon i.e., two nuclei \r\n     from two protoplasm, cohabit but does not fuse.  \r\n5. Later karyogamy occurs resulting in diploid cells.  \r\n6.Meiosis of diploid cells to form haploid spores occurs in the fruiting body of the fungi (Ascospores/Basidiospores).\r\n7. These spores can be dispersed and can germinate into new mycelium.\r\n \r\n'),
('OSTEICHTHYES  (The Bony Fishes)', 'GENERAL FEATURES:\r\n1. Cold blooded animals, exoskeleton, comprises cycloid, ctenoid, ganoid scales(dermal in origin),occur in fresh, marine, brackish water.\r\n2. Caudal fin or tail fin homocercal (symmetrical);mouth terminal, digestive tract complete, cloaca absent.\r\n3. External nares on dorsal surface, internal nares also preent,4 pairs of gills covered by operculum.\r\n4. Heart-2 chambered, swim bladder(air bladder) for balancing body and also for respiration. Exception: Lung fish(3chambered fish).    \r\n'),
('OSTEICHTHYES  (The Bony Fishes)', 'GENERAL FEATURES:\r\n1. Cold blooded animals, exoskeleton, comprises cycloid, ctenoid, ganoid scales(dermal in origin),occur in fresh, marine, brackish water.\r\n2. Caudal fin or tail fin homocercal (symmetrical);mouth terminal, digestive tract complete, cloaca absent.\r\n3. External nares on dorsal surface, internal nares also preent,4 pairs of gills covered by operculum.\r\n4. Heart-2 chambered, swim bladder(air bladder) for balancing body and also for respiration. Exception: Lung fish(3chambered fish).    \r\n'),
('Osteichthyes (बोनी फिश)', 'सामान्य सुविधाएँ:\r\n1.  ठंडे खून वाले जानवर, एक्सोस्केलेटन, जिसमें साइक्लोइड, केटेनॉइड, गैनॉइड स्केल (मूल रूप से त्वचीय) शामिल हैं, ताजे, समुद्री, खारे पानी में होते हैं।\r\n2.  कॉडल फिन या टेल फिन होमोकेरकल (सममित); माउथ टर्मिनल, पाचन तंत्र पूर्ण, क्लोका अनुपस्थित।\r\n3.  पृष्ठीय सतह पर बाहरी नारियाँ, आंतरिक नारियाँ भी दिखाई देती हैं, 4 जोड़ी गलफड़े ओपेरकुलम से ढके होते हैं।\r\n4.  शरीर को संतुलित करने और श्वसन के लिए भी हृदय-2 कक्षीय, तैरने वाला मूत्राशय (वायु मूत्राशय)। अपवाद: फेफड़े की मछली (3 कक्षीय मछली)।'),
('EXAMPLES OF BONY FISHES:', '1. carp\r\n2. Cat Fish\r\n3. Murrels\r\n4. Labeo rohita\r\n'),
('बोनी मछलियों के उदाहरण:', '1. कार्प\r\n2. कैट फिश\r\n3. मुर्रेल्स\r\n4. लबियो रोहिता\r\n'),
('Amphibia(vertebrates with dual life)', 'General  features:\r\n1. Cold blooded vertebrates, amphibious, in nature(land + water)\r\n2. Body divisible into head and trunk; tail may or may not be present.\r\n3. Scales generally absent; if present hidden beneath the skin; skin is smooth or rough with glands to keep it moist.\r\n4. Unpaired fins present; two pair of limbs for locomotion.\r\n5. Gills present in larval stage(external gills).\r\n6. Respiration through lungs, skin, gills, buccopharyngeal cavity.\r\n7. Heart 3 chambered with well developed hepatic and renal portal systems.\r\n'),
('Extra features of Amphibia(vertebrates with dual life)', '1. Endoskeleton bony, skull flat and dicondylic. Dicondylic means bear two occipital condyles and skull is connected by 1st vertebral column with \r\n     this condyles.\r\n2. Kidneys, urinary bladder in frog present. Larva and tailed amphibians ammonoteic, frogs and toads are ureotelic.\r\n3. Alimentary canal, urinary tract, reproductive tract open into a common opening cloaca that further opens into cloacal aperture.\r\n4. Internal, middle ear present, tympanum(outer membrane) cover middle ear; eyes with eyelids, nictitating membrane present.\r\n5. Lateral line system present during their development.\r\n6.  Fertilization internal, oviparous and some viviparous; development indirect; male lacks copulatory organs. Metamorphosis present; fish like larva \r\n      tadpole is present, they return to water for breeding.\r\n\r\n'),
(' उभयचर (दोहरे जीवन वाले कशेरुकी)', 'सामान्य सुविधाएँ:\r\n\r\n1.  ठंडे रक्त वाले कशेरुकी, उभयचर, प्रकृति में (भूमि + जल)\r\n2.  शरीर सिर और धड़ में विभाजित; पूंछ मौजूद हो सकती है या नहीं भी हो सकती है।\r\n3. तराजू आम तौर पर अनुपस्थित; अगर त्वचा के नीचे छिपा हुआ है; त्वचा नम रखने के लिए ग्रंथियों के साथ चिकनी या खुरदरी होती है।\r\n4.  अयुग्मित पंख मौजूद; हरकत के लिए दो जोड़ी अंग।\r\n5.  लार्वा चरण (बाहरी गलफड़े) में मौजूद गलफड़े।\r\n6.  फेफड़े, त्वचा, गलफड़ों, बुकोफैरेनजीज गुहा के माध्यम से श्वसन।\r\n7.  हृदय 3 सुविकसित यकृत और वृक्क पोर्टल प्रणालियों से युक्त है।\r\n\r\n'),
(' उभयचर की अतिरिक्त विशेषताएं (दोहरे जीवन वाले कशेरुकी)', '1. एंडोस्केलेटन बोनी, खोपड़ी फ्लैट और डाइकॉन्डिलिक। डाइकॉन्डिलिक का अर्थ है दो पश्चकपाल शंकुधारी और खोपड़ी 1 कशेरुक स्तंभ द्वारा जुड़ी हुई है यह \r\n    condyles.\r\n2. मेंढक में गुर्दे, मूत्राशय उपस्थित होते हैं। लार्वा और पूंछ वाले उभयचर अमोनोटिक, मेंढक और टोड यूरेटेलिक हैं।\r\n3. एलिमेंटरी कैनाल, मूत्र पथ, प्रजनन पथ एक सामान्य उद्घाटन क्लोअका में खुलते हैं जो आगे चलकर क्लोएकल एपर्चर में खुलते हैं।\r\n4. आंतरिक, मध्य कान मौजूद, टाइम्पेनम (बाहरी झिल्ली) मध्य कान को कवर करता है; पलकों के साथ आंखें, निक्टिटेटिंग मेम्ब्रेन मौजूद है।\r\n5. उनके विकास के दौरान मौजूद लेटरल लाइन सिस्टम।\r\n6. निषेचन आंतरिक, अंडाकार और कुछ जीवित; विकास अप्रत्यक्ष; पुरुष में मैथुन संबंधी अंगों की कमी होती है। कायापलट मौजूद; लार्वा जैसी मछली टैडपोल मौजूद हैं, वे प्रजनन के लिए पानी में लौट आते हैं।\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n'),
('सरीसृप (रेंगने वाले कशेरुकी)', 'सामान्य सुविधाएँ:\r\n1. शीत-रक्त वाले, रेंगने वाले और दफनाने वाले कशेरुक, एपिडर्मल तराजू की उपस्थिति।\r\n2. कुछ ठंडे स्थानों में, ज्यादातर गर्म क्षेत्रों, स्थलीय जानवरों में रहते हैं।\r\n3. त्वचा शुष्क, खुरदरी, बिना ग्रंथियों वाली, कुछ सरीसृपों द्वारा त्वचा की ढलाई।\r\n4. खोपड़ी मोनरोन्डिलिक है।\r\n5. सांपों को छोड़कर, पेंटाडैक्टाइल अंगों के 2 जोड़े जिनमें से प्रत्येक में पांच अंकों वाले पंजे होते हैं।\r\n'),
('सरीसृप की अतिरिक्त विशेषताएं (रेंगने वाले कशेरुकी)', '1. पसलियां मौजूद हैं, फेफड़ों के माध्यम से श्वसन, हृदय में दो अलिंद और अपूर्ण रूप से   विभाजित वेंट्रिकल (अपूर्ण रूप से 4 कक्षीय हृदय) होते हैं।\r\n2. गुर्दे, मूत्राशय मौजूद। मगरमच्छ (अमोनोटेलिक); कछुए, घड़ियाल(यूरोटेलिक); छिपकली और सांप (यूरिकोटेलिक), क्लोअका मौजूद है।\r\n3. कान 3 भागों के साथ: बाहरी, मध्य, आंतरिक। सांप अपवाद।\r\n4. पार्श्व रेखा प्रणाली अनुपस्थित।\r\n5. सरीसृप मांसाहारी, कीटभक्षी होते हैं लेकिन कुछ वनस्पति पर भोजन करते हैं। उदाहरण: कछुआ।\r\n6. ओविपेरस, विविपेरस, निषेचन आंतरिक, नर में मैथुन अंग होते हैं, अंडे सूखी भूमि पर रखे जाते हैं।\r\n7. दोनों दोषों में दांतों के साथ मुंह बड़ा, जीभ बाहर निकल सकती है या नहीं, पूर्ण पाचन तंत्र।\r\n\r\n\r\n'),
('Aves(The Birds)', ': General features:\r\n1.	Warm blooded animals, have coat of feathers and resting on hind limb alone so called feathered bipeds.\r\n2.	Two pair of limbs: forelimb and hind limb.\r\n	Forelimb :- modified into wings for flight.\r\n	Hind limb :- support the body, walking, griping, swimming. \r\n  legs bear horny epidermal scales, each hand has only three digits.\r\n3.	Additional chambers in alimentary canal i.e. crop and gizzard. Crop-stores and soften the food. Gizzard-muscular to crush and churn the soften food. Upper and lower jaws modified the beak(without teeth ) that helps in feeding.\r\n4.	Body boat shaped, streamlined, divisible into head, neck, trunk, tail; presence of four chambered heart.\r\n5.	Skin thin, dry except on the tail it bears preen or oil gland, pectin present in the eyes, ear bear three parts, keen eyesight.\r\n6.	Brain better than reptiles, skull monocondylic, brain bear optic lobes, cerebellum, reduced olfactory lobes\r\n7.	Long hollow bones present with air cavity(pneumatic bones) to reduce weight; sternum with a median keel to attach the flight muscle.\r\n'),
('एव्स (पक्षी)', 'सामान्य सुविधाएँ:\r\n\r\n\r\n1. गर्म रक्त वाले जानवर, पंखों का कोट होते हैं और केवल हिंद अंग पर आराम करते हैं, तथाकथित पंख वाले द्विपाद।\r\n\r\n2. दो जोड़ी अंग: अग्र अंग और हिंद अंग।\r\nForelimb: उड़ान के लिए पंखों में संशोधित।\r\nहिंद अंग :- शरीर को सहारा देना, चलना, पकड़ना, तैरना।\r\n             पैरों में सींग वाले एपिडर्मल तराजू होते हैं, प्रत्येक हाथ में केवल तीन अंक होते हैं।\r\n\r\n3. आहार नाल में अतिरिक्त कक्ष अर्थात फसल और गिजार्ड। फसल-भंडार और भोजन को नरम करना। नरम भोजन को कुचलने और मथने के लिए गिजार्ड-पेशी।\r\n ऊपरी और निचले जबड़े चोंच (बिना दांतों के) को संशोधित करते हैं जो खिलाने में मदद करते हैं।\r\n\r\n4. शरीर की नाव के आकार का, सुव्यवस्थित, सिर, गर्दन, धड़, पूंछ में विभाज्य; चार कक्षीय हृदय की उपस्थिति।\r\n\r\n५. त्वचा पतली, सूखी होती है सिवाय इसके कि पूँछ पर प्रीन या तेल ग्रंथि होती है, आँखों में पेक्टिन होता है, कान के तीन भाग होते हैं, तीव्र दृष्टि होती है।\r\n\r\n6. मस्तिष्क सरीसृप से बेहतर है, खोपड़ी मोनोकॉन्डिलिक, मस्तिष्क भालू ऑप्टिक लोब, सेरिबैलम, कम घ्राण लोब\r\n\r\n7. वजन कम करने के लिए वायु गुहा (वायवीय हड्डियों) के साथ मौजूद लंबी खोखली हड्डियां; उरोस्थि एक मध्य कील के साथ उड़ान पेशी संलग्न करने के लिए।\r\n'),
('8.	Mammalia(The Mammals)', 'General features:\r\n1.	Warm blooded, hairy, presence of mammary glands, body divisible into head, neck, trunk, tail.\r\n2.	Presence of two pairs of pentadactyl limbs for jumping, climbing, swimming, etc.; bear horny claws, nails, hoofs.\r\n3.	Teeth of different types(heterodont) and are embedded in the sockets of jaws(thecodont). Milk and permanent teeth occur in two sets(diphyodont).\r\n4.	Presence of sebaceous(oil) glands, sudoriferous glands(sweat) in the skin; salivary glands in buccal cavity.\r\n5.	Lungs spongy, elastic; ribs muscles and diaphragm play role in breathing.\r\n6.	Skull dicondylic; movable eyelids; ear with three regions. Internal, middle, external ear. Organ of corti(internal ear); middle ear three bones: malleus, incus, stapes.  External ear fleshy pimma.\r\n7.	Kidney bean-shaped; uterus open into urinary bladder; urea as excretory waste.\r\n'),
('स्तनधारी', 'उत्तर सामान्य विशेषताएं:\r\n1. गर्म रक्तयुक्त, बालों वाली, स्तन ग्रंथियों की उपस्थिति, शरीर सिर, गर्दन, धड़, पूंछ में विभाजित।\r\n2. कूदने, चढ़ने, तैरने आदि के लिए दो जोड़ी पेंटाडैक्टाइल अंगों की उपस्थिति; सींग वाले पंजे, नाखून, खुर धारण करें।\r\n3. विभिन्न प्रकार के दांत (हेटरोडोंट) और जबड़ों (दकोडोंट) के सॉकेट में एम्बेडेड होते हैं। दूध और स्थायी दांत दो सेट (डिप्योडोंट) में होते हैं।\r\n4. त्वचा में वसामय (तेल) ग्रंथियों, सूदक ग्रंथियों (पसीना) की उपस्थिति; मुख गुहा में लार ग्रंथियां।\r\n5. फेफड़े स्पंजी, लोचदार; पसलियों की मांसपेशियां और डायाफ्राम सांस लेने में भूमिका निभाते हैं।\r\n6. खोपड़ी डाइकॉन्डिलिक; चल पलकें; तीन क्षेत्रों के साथ कान। आंतरिक, मध्य, बाहरी कान। कोर्टी का अंग (आंतरिक कान); मध्य कान की तीन हड्डियाँ: मैलियस, इन्कस, स्टेपीज़। बाहरी कान मांसल पिम्मा।\r\n'),
(' NUCLEOLUS', 'Boman gave the discovery=explanation and nomenclature.  \r\n\r\n1. It  is a membrane less structure \r\n2. The factory of ribosome is called \"  NUCLEOLUS \".\r\n3. Function – Synthesis of proteins\r\n\r\n'),
('केंद्रिका ', 'खोज=फोंटना तथा नामकरण बोमन ने दिया |  \r\n\r\n1.यह एक झिल्ली  रहित  सरंचना हैं |\r\n2. राइबोसोम का कारखाना “केंद्रिका” को  ही कहा जाता है |\r\n3. कार्य –प्रोटीन का संश्लेषण         करना\r\n4.  रासायनिक संगठन \r\n'),
('Definition of State', 'With a few exceptions, all the fundamental rights are available against the State. \r\n•	Under Article 12, unless the context otherwise requires, “the State” includes –\r\n•	 (a) the Government and Parliament of India; \r\n•	(b) the Government and Legislature of each of the States; and \r\n•	(c) all local or other authorities :- (i) within the territory of India; or (ii) under the control of the Government of India.\r\n•	The expression ‘local authorities’ refers to authorities like Municipalities, \r\n•	District Boards, Panchayats, Improvement Trusts, Port Trusts and Mining \r\n•	Settlement Boards.\r\n•	The Supreme Court has held that ‘other authorities’ will include all authorities created by the Constitution or statute on whom powers are conferred by law and it is not necessary that the authority should engage in performing government functions (Electricity Board, Rajasthan v. Mohanlal, AIR 1967 SC 1957). \r\n'),
('', ''),
('', ''),
('', ''),
('Organisms and populations', 'Ecology:- (oaks - homes; logos-study)\r\n	Ernst Hackle coined the term ecology.\r\n	Humboldt \" father of ecology \".\r\n	It is a branch of science that deals with the  inter- relationship among organisms and interaction between organisms and their environment. \r\n	Sub-division of ecology are:-\r\n	(a) Autecology/ species Ecology:- study of individual species in relation to the environment.  It includes study of life history,  behaviour,  \r\n            morphological features,  population, taxonomic positions , reproduction.\r\n	(b) Synecology/Ecosystem ecology:- study of group of organisms or population interacting among themselves or with the environment.  It \r\n           includes group of interbreeding species,  various kinds of competition,  predation,  how to conserve species, more complex than autecology.  \r\n'),
('Autecology/ species Ecology', 'Study of individual species in relation to the environment.  It includes study of life history,  behaviour,  morphological features,  population, taxonomic positions , reproduction.'),
('Synecology/Ecosystem ecology', 'Study of group of organisms or population interacting among themselves or with the environment.  It includes group of interbreeding species,  various kinds of competition,  predation,  how to conserve species, more complex than autecology.  \r\n\r\n'),
('What is an Organism/ Individual:- ?', 'Individual is made up of cells ; can have unicellular or multicellular body. \r\n	It is a basic unit of ecological hierarchy as it is continuously exchanging materials from surrounding.  \r\n	It has a fixed life span, growth, maturity,  old age and death. \r\n	It arises from pre-existing organisms through reproduction \r\n	Organisms are greatly influenced by surrounding and fluctuating environments.  So, being dynamic they are will adapted to their environment.  \r\n\r\n'),
('Population:- ', 'Group of individuals of same kind present in a particular geographical area at a particular time- population. \r\n	Ex:- All the frugs (Rana tigerina) living in a given pond for population. \r\n	The different population of  same organism present in particular geographical area- Local population or domestic. \r\n	Example:- Home sapiens (humans) living in hills, plains and islands form different population.\r\n\r\n\r\n'),
('Community', 'Organisms of all in population that live in a particular area and interact with one another is called Biological or Biotic community. \r\n	Various biotic communities are animals community,  plant community, microbial community. \r\n	Biotic community best example is forest.\r\n\r\n'),
('Ecosystem:-', 'Interactions of community and its physical environment for exchanging materials as well as energy.  Example:- Pond ecosystem,  forest ecosystem.\r\n	Interactions can be intro specific ( Between members of different species) and Interspecific (Between members of same species\r\n'),
('Biome', ': Biomed are the areas of the world having specific climatic zone, vegetation zone and its associated flora and fauna. \r\nMajor terrestrial biomes are:-\r\n\r\n	A. Tundra.\r\n	B. Coniferous forests \r\n	C. Deciduous forests \r\n	D. Grasslands \r\n	E. Desert\r\n'),
('Biosphere', 'Also called ecosphere.  Global ecosystem with biotic and biotic components.'),
('Organisms and its Environment ', 'Physiological ecology helps us to understand how different organisms are adapted in their environment and how they undergo reproduction. \r\n\r\n2.  Rotation of earth and the tilt of its axis causes seasonal changes which leads to formation of major terrestrial biomed of the world.\r\n\r\n	. Major terrestrial biomes are:- \r\n	A. Tundra.\r\n	B. Coniferous forests \r\n	C. Deciduous forests \r\n	D. Grasslands \r\n	E. Desert. \r\n\r\n\r\n'),
('Tundra:-', 'Tundra:-\r\n	(a) occurs in the Arctic region.  Hence called artic  tundra; lies towards north side \r\n	(b) Absent in the southern hemisphere. \r\n	(C) Receives little precipitation; are covered by snow; ground remains in frozen (perma frost) condition. \r\n	(d) Also called artic desert as it contains very low growing vegetation (devoid of trees) . \r\n	(e) Flora:- Lichens and Mosses,  grasses,  low shrubs. \r\n	Fauna:- Amphibians, reptiles Absent; polar bear,  arctic fox, musk ox , water birds,  present..\r\n\r\n\r\n'),
('Coniferous forests:- (Taiga)', 'Coniferous forests:- (Taiga)\r\n\r\n(a) occur just south to tundra across North America and also is southern hemisphere  ( New Zealand)\r\n(b) snowfall occur very heavily;  Lakes and  Marshes present. \r\n(C) Summer is mild; winter chilly with long dark nights \r\n(D) Fauna :- Rabbit,  Deer, Wolves, Flk,  pumas,  grouse. \r\nFlora:- Juniper,  Pines,  Fir,  Vines,  and wild flowers,  herbs, ferns, mosses,  and lichens.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n');
