1.Papillae- raised structures occurs on the lips located at anterior end and on cloacal aperture. They are tectile (Touch)\r\n   (b)  Amphids:- apits present on the lips and are chemoreceptors.\r\n   (c)   Phasmids:- Unicellular glands and are glandulosensory in nature.\r\n10. Excretary system: Present of gland cells or Intracellular canals. Ammonia and urea Excretary waste. Ascaris (urea and Ammonia).\r\n11. Reproduction: Sexes separate ( dioecious); females are longer than males (sexual dimorphism); Assexual reproduction absent; Fertilization \r\n      internal; development through larval stages or direct.'),
('features and habitat of Phylum Aschelminths/Nemathelminths (Roundworms).', 'ANS :  General Features:-\r\n\r\n1.Habitat: Parasites Plants and Animals, causes agriculture veterinary and health problems. Free living\r\n\r\n 2.Body form: Unsegmented, cylindrical tapering at both ends.\r\n\r\n3 Body wall and cavity: Consists of non-living cuticle, syncytial epidermis (Multi nucleated cytoplasm), Muscle layer present, cilia absent. Pseudocoelom present filled with Pseudocelli fluid.\r\n\r\n4.Germ layer: Triploblastic\r\n\r\n5.Symmetry and level of organization: Bilateral symmetry and organ-system level of organization.\r\n\r\n6.Skeleton: High fluid pressure in the pseudocoelom maintained body shape (hydro skeleton).\r\n\r\n7.Digestive tract: Complete type; with & muscular pharynx and non- muscular intestine.\r\n\r\n8.Respiratory and circulatory system: Respiration through body surface by diffusion and circulatory system absent.\r\n\r\n9.Nervous system and sense organs: Have cricopharyngeal ring that give rise to nerves forward as well as backward.\r\n\r\nSense organs: -\r\n\r\n1.Papillae- raised structures occurs on the lips located at anterior end and on cloacal aperture. They are tactile (Touch)\r\n2.Amphids:- a pits present on the lips and are chemoreceptors.\r\n3.Phasmids:- Unicellular glands and are glandulosensory in nature.\r\n10.Excretary system: Present of gland cells or Intracellular canals. Ammonia and urea Excretory waste. Ascaris (urea and Ammonia).\r\n11.Reproduction: Sexes separate (dioecious); females are longer than males (sexual dimorphism); Asexual reproduction absent; Fertilization internal; development through larval stages or direct.\r\n\r\n'),
(' features of Phylum Annelids (segmented animals).', 'General Features:-\r\n\r\n1.Habitat: fresh water, sea water, moist soil, burrowing animals and few parasitic.\r\n\r\n2.Body form: Metameric segmentation. Its segment-Peristomium and above it out growth is called  prostomium.\r\n \r\n3.Body wall and cavity: wall thin, moist cuticle, single layer spider mis, circular and longitudinal muscles (helps in locomotion). True coelom present. coelomic fluid form hydro skeleton.\r\n\r\n4.symmetry and level or organization: Bilateral symmetry and organ-system level of organization.\r\n\r\n5.Germ layer: Triploblastic\r\n\r\n6.Digestive system: Complete\r\n\r\n7.Circulatory system: closed circulatory system. Coelomic fluid and space modified to form this system. i.e.Haemocoelomic System With Haemocoelomic fluid. Blood is red due to Hemoglobin\r\n\r\n8.Respiratory system: Gaseous exchange through skin (Cutaneous respiration) and through gills (Branchial respiratory)\r\n\r\n9.Excretory system: Coiled, tubular structures (Nephridia) help in osmoregulation and exertion. In aquatic form (Ammonia-excretory waste) and in land form (Urea)\r\n\r\n10.Nervous system and sense organs: consists or nerve ring;\r\n'),
('features or habitat of Phylum Porifera (Pore bearing animals)?', 'General Features: -\r\n	1.Habitat: Sponges like warm water, sessile (attached to substratum), aquatic, marine, fresh water.\r\n\r\n        2.Body form: Body porous, water transport or Canal System water enter through ostia (inhalant pores) ➡️Central \r\n               Cavity(spongocoel)➡️Osculum (Exhalent pores)\r\n\r\n        3.Symmetry and level of organization: Asymmetrical and Cellular level of organization.\r\n\r\n        4.Germ layers: Diploblastic animals.\r\n\r\n        5.Body wall: Three layers: -\r\n\r\n1.Pinacoderm (Dermal layer)\r\n2. Choanoderm (Gastral layer)\r\n3. Mesophyll layer (Mesenchymee)\r\n\r\n6.Skeleton: Internal Skeleton (calcareous spicules or silicious and spongin fibres) located in Mesenchyme.\r\n\r\n7.Digestion: Intracellular (takes place inside food vacuoles)\r\n\r\n8.Respiration and Excretion: By diffusion through plasma membrane\r\n\r\n9.Circulation: Mesenchymee amoeboid cells help in food distribution.\r\n\r\n10.Reproduction: Sexual reproduction; Asexual reproduction (Budding); Basically sponges(hermaphrodite); Fertilization internal.\r\n\r\n'),
('features of Phylum Coelenterate/Cnidaria (Sac like animals + Sting Cells)?', 'General Features: -\r\n	1.Habitat: Aquatic, mostly marine, Hydra (fresh water)\r\n\r\n	2.Body form: Two body form or zooids: - Polyp and Medusa\r\n\r\n	 Polyp:- Sessile, Cylindrical , Solitary\r\n\r\n	 Medusa: -Umbrella Luke, free-swimming, solitary\r\n\r\n	 Polymorphism: -Polyp and medusa both are present in single species and many have subtypes and different functions.\r\n\r\n3.Symmetry and level of organization: Radial symmetry and tissue level of organization.\r\n\r\n4.Germ Layer: Diploblastic animals\r\n\r\n5.Body Wall: Have two layers of cells:-Epidermis(Outer) and Gastrodermis(Inner); Mesoglea(Non-Cellular gelatinous layer)\r\n\r\n1.Epidermis:-Nerve Cells, Interstitial/Totipotent cells; Sensory cells; Epitheliomuscular cells(Protective + Muscles); Stinging cells(Endoblasts or Nematocyst).\r\n\r\n Entoblaste:- consists of capsule shaft and thread tube.\r\n\r\n2.Gastrdermis:-Digestive cells, Gland cells, Nerve and Sensory cells.\r\n\r\n6.Skeleton: Calcareous Endo-Exoskeleton\r\n\r\n7.Respiration and Excretion: By diffusion, Ammonia(excretory waste)\r\n\r\n8.Digestive System: Intra-Extra cellular digestion; have coelenteron (a central gastrovascular cavity) with a hypostome (mouth) and have blind sac plan.\r\n\r\n9.Nervous system: Primitive form of nervous system i.e. Statocysts(Balancing organ) \r\n\r\n10.Reproduction: Asexual reproduction (Budding) in polyp form and sexual  reproduction in medusa form. Gonads (with no ducts)\r\nMetagenesis: -\r\nPolyp reproduce *asexually➡️* Medusa\r\nMedusa reproduce *sexually➡️* Polyp.\r\nSuch, alteration of asexual and sexual phase in life cycle of obelia is called Metagenesis. Cnidarians also have power of regeneration.\r\n'),
('features of Phylum Porifera (Pore bearing animals)', 'General Features: -\r\n1.Habitat: Sponges like warm water, sessile (attached to substratum), aquatic, marine, fresh water.\r\n\r\n2.Body form: Body porous, water transport or Canal System water enter through ostia (inhalant pores) ➡️Central Cavity \r\n      (spongocoel)➡️Osculum (Exhalent pores).\r\n\r\n3.Symmetry and level of organization: Asymmetrical and Cellular level of organization.\r\n\r\n4.Germ layers: Diploblastic animals.\r\n\r\n5.Body wall: Three layers: -\r\n\r\n1.Pinacoderm (Dermal layer)\r\n2. Choanoderm (Gastral layer)\r\n3. Mesophyll layer (Mesenchyme)\r\n\r\n6.Skeleton: Internal Skeleton (calcareous spicules or siliceous and spongin fibers) located in Mesenchyme.\r\n\r\n7.Digestion: Intracellular (takes place inside food vacuoles)\r\n\r\n8.Respiration and Excretion: By diffusion through plasma membrane\r\n\r\n9.Circulation: Mesenchyme amoeboid cells help in food distribution.\r\n\r\n10.Reproduction: Sexual reproduction; Asexual reproduction (Budding); Basically sponges(hermaphrodite); Fertilization internal.\r\n'),
('features of Phylum Colenterata/Cnidaria (Sac like animals + Sting Cells)', 'Personnel and Trembly recognized cnidarians as animals. \r\nLeuckart termed as coelenterate.\r\n\r\nGeneral Features:-\r\n\r\n1. Habitat: Aquatic, mostly marine, Hydra(fresh water)\r\n\r\n2. Body form :Two body form or zooids:- Polyp and Medusa\r\n Polyp:- Sessile, Cylindrical, Solitary\r\n Medusa:-Umbrella like , free-swimming, solitary\r\n Polymorphism:-Polyp and medusa both are present in single species and many have subtypes and different functions.\r\n\r\n3. Symmetry and level of organization: Radial symmetry and tissue level of organization.\r\n\r\n4. Germ Layer: Diploblastic animals.\r\n\r\n5. Body Wall: Have two layers of cells:-Epidermis(Outer) and Gastrodermis(Inner); Mesogloea(Non-Cellular gelatinous layer).\r\n\r\n1. Epidermis:-Nerve Cells, Interstitial/Totipotent cells; Sensory cells;  Epithelium Muscular cells(Protective + Muscles); Stinging cells(Cnidoblast or \r\n       Nematocyst).\r\n   Nematoblast:- consists of capsule shaft and thread tube.\r\n2. Gastrodermis:-Digestive cells, Gland cells, Nerve and Sensory cells\r\n\r\n6. Skeleton: Calcareous Endo-Exoskeleton.\r\n\r\n7. Respiration and Excretion: By diffusion, Ammonia(excretory waste).\r\n\r\n8. Digestive System: Intra-Extra cellular digestion; have coelenteron (a central gastrovascular cavity) with a hypostome (mouth) and have blind sac \r\n    plan.\r\n\r\n9. Nervous system: Primitive form of nervous system. i.e  Statocyst(Balancing organ)'),
('features of habitat of Phylum Ctenophora (The comb Jellies or Sea Walnuts).', ' Eichholtz recognized ctenophora as animals.\r\n\r\nGeneral Features:-\r\n\r\n1.Habitat: Marine feed on plankton, swimming (cilia),Bioluminescence (Property of emitting light).\r\n\r\n2.Body form: Variable, tentacles (may or may not be present).If present two in number.\r\n\r\n3.Symmetry: Radial symmetry (Comb plates); Bilateral symmetry(Tentacles and Branching)\r\n\r\n4.Level of organization: Tissue level of organization and Acoelomates.\r\n\r\n5.Germ layer: Diploblastic animals.\r\n\r\n6.Body Wall: Epidermis(outer), Gastrodermis( Inner), Mesalo, (Middle also called Collenchyma), Colloblasts (Lasso cells) in epidermis of tentacles \r\n   of capture food.\r\n\r\n7.Locomotion: Comb like right ciliary plates- comb plates helps in swimming so, called comb jellies.\r\n\r\n8.Digestive system: Also called Gastrovascular tract include, mouth, pharynx,  stomodeum, stomach or Infundibulum, anal canals, two and pores. Complete digestive system. Digestion can be Extra or Intracellular (food  vacuole).\r\n\r\n9.Absence of skeletal, circulatory, Respiratory and Excretory system.\r\n\r\n10.Nervous system: statocyst present at aboral end.\r\n\r\n11.Reproduction:Hermaphrodite (Bisexual or Monecious);Asexual reproduction  absent; Fertilization external; Paedogenesis is common \r\n      (Paedogenesis means larva reproduce another larva).\r\n\r\n(Mesogloea consists of smooth muscles and amoebocytes.)\r\n\r\n'),
('features of Phylum Platyhelminthes (Flat worms).', 'Gegenuber gave the term Platyhelminthes.\r\n\r\nGeneral Features:-\r\n1. Habitat: Parasites (with hooks and suckers) ,free-living  (Marine, freshwater, Terrestrial).\r\n\r\n2. Body form: Dorsoventrally flattened, no true segments.\r\n\r\n3. Symmetry and level of organization: Bilateral symmetry and organ-system level of organization.\r\n\r\n4. Germ layer: Triploblastic and Acoelomates animals.\r\n\r\n5. Body wall: Body soft, with or without cilia.\r\n\r\n(a).  Rhabdites(Rod-shaped cells) in epidermal cells to capture food. \r\n(b). Parenchyma( Space fill between body wall and organs) that help in transpiration of food material and also help in maintaining body shape \r\n         (Hydroskeleton).\r\n\r\n6.Absence of skeletal system, Respiratory system, Circulatory system.\r\n\r\n7.Excretory system: Flame cells (Solenocytes or Protonephridia) helps in excretion, Ammonia(Excretory waste).\r\n\r\n8.Digestive system: Incomplete.\r\n\r\n9.Nervous system: ladder like nervous system include two longitudinal nerve cord connected by transverse commissures at several intervals.\r\n\r\n10.Reproduction: Hermaphrodite; fertilization (Internal); Asexual reproduction by Binary fission. Development through larval stages i.e. \r\n    Miracidium, sporocyst, Redia, Cercaria, Meter Cercaria larva.\r\n\r\n'),
('features of Phylum Aschelminthes/Nemathelminths (Round worms)', 'Geganbour gave the term Aschelminthes\r\n\r\nGeneral Features:-\r\n\r\n1.Habitat: Parasites Plants and Animals, causes agriculture veterinary and health problems. Free living.\r\n\r\n2.Body form: Unsegmented, cylindrical tapering at both ends.\r\n\r\n3 Body wall and cavity: Consists of non-living cuticle, syncytial epidermis(Multi nucleated cytoplasm), Muscle layer present, cilia absent.  \r\n    Pseudocoelom present filled with Pseducoelmic fluid.\r\n\r\n4.Germ layer: Triploblastic.\r\n\r\n5.Symmetry and level of organization: Bilateral symmetry and organ-system level of organization.\r\n\r\n6.Skeleton: High fluid pressure in the  pseudocoelom maintenance body shape (Hydroskeleton).\r\n\r\n7.Digestive tract: Complete type; with & muscular pharynx and non- muscular intestine.\r\n\r\n8.Respiratory and circulatory system: Respiration through body surface by diffusion and circulatory system absent.\r\n\r\n9.Nervous system and sense organs: Have circumpharyngeal ring that give rise to nerves forward as well as backward.\r\n   Sense organs:-\r\n1.Papillae- raised structures occurs on the lips located at anterior end and on cloacal aperture. They are tactile (Touch).\r\n2.Amphids:- pits present on the lips and are chemoreceptors.\r\n3.Phasmids:- Unicellular glands and are glandulosensory in nature.\r\n\r\n10. Excretory system: Present of gland cells or Intracellular canals. Ammonia and urea Excretory waste. Ascaris (urea and Ammonia).\r\n\r\n11. Reproduction: Sexes separate ( dioecious); females are longer than males (sexual dimorphism); Asexual reproduction absent; Fertilization \r\n     internal; development through larval stages or direct.'),
('features of Phylum Annelids (segmented animals)', 'Lamarck gave the term Annelids.\r\n\r\nGeneral Features:-\r\n\r\n1.Habitat: fresh water, sea water, moist soil, burrowing animals and few parasitic.\r\n\r\n2.Body form: Metameric segmentation. First segment-Peristomium and above it out growth is called prostomium. \r\n\r\n3.Body wall and cavity: wall thin, moist cuticle, single layer epidermis, circular and longitudinal muscles(helps in locomotion). True coelom present. coelomic fluid form hydroskeleton.\r\n\r\n4.symmetry and level or organization: Bilateral symmetry and organ-system level of organization.\r\n\r\n5.Germ layer: Triploblastic.\r\n\r\n6.Digestive system: Complete.\r\n\r\n7.Circulatory system: closed circulatory system. Coelomic fluid and space modified to form this system. i.e. Haemocoelomic System or hemocoelic \r\n   system with Haemocoelomic fluid. Blood is red due to Hemoglobin.\r\n\r\n8.Respiratory system: Gaseous exchange through skin (Cutaneous respiration) and through gills (Branchial respiratory).\r\n\r\n9.Excretory system: Coiled, tubular structures (Nephridia) helps in osmoregulation and exertion. In aquatic form(Ammonia-excretory waste) and in land form (Urea).\r\n\r\n10.Nervous system and sense organs: consists or nerve ring;\r\n'),
('FIVE KINGDOM CLASSIFICATION', 'R H Whittaker in 1969 proposed five kingdom classification. Earlier, scientists have considered the presence of cell wall as one of the major factors for classification. Hence, bacteria, blue-green algae, fungi, mosses, ferns, gymnosperms, and angiosperms were altogether grouped under ‘Plantae’. The anomaly in such classification is that all the prokaryotic bacteria, blue-green algae and other eukaryotes which differ in their cellular organization, cell wall composition and organisms with varied modes of nutrition, despite their significant differences, were classified under a single kingdom. Whittaker had corrected the anomaly by considering other factors like cell type, nature of cell wall, nuclear membrane, body organization, mode of nutrition to classify the organisms across five kingdoms much accurately lessening the differences to a level minimum.'),
('Classification of the five kingdoms.', '1. Monera \r\n\r\nBased on the shape bacteria can be categorized as :\r\n1. Cocci: Spherical shaped\r\n2. Bacilli: Rod shaped\r\n3. Vibrium: Comma-shaped\r\n4. Spirillum: spiral \r\n5. Spirochaete: corkscrew shaped\r\n\r\n2. Protista\r\n\r\na. Single celled Eukaryotes.\r\n\r\nb. Mostly aquatic with well-defined nucleus with histone DNA and membrane bound organelles.\r\n\r\nc. Few have cilia or flagella with 9+2 organization of microtubules having tubulin. \r\n \r\nd. Reproduce both asexually through binary fission and sexually through cell fusion and zygote formation.\r\n\r\ne. They obtain energy through autotrophic holophytic mode i.e. vide photosynthesis in presence of light and heterotrophic holozoic mode i.e., vide \r\n     ingestion of inorganic material in absence of light.\r\n\r\n3. Fungi\r\n\r\na. Heterotrophic organisms depending on either dead substrates (Saprophytic) or on plants and animals (parasitic) with rich diversity in morphology \r\n     and habitat.\r\nb. Few fungi live in association with algae as Lichens and with roots of plants as Mycorrhiza through symbiotic relation. \r\nc. They are cosmopolitan and present in air, water, soil, animals and plants and mostly found at damp places. \r\nd.  Few fungi are pathogenic and infects animals, plants etc. \r\ne.   Principal decomposers in ecological systems. \r\nf.    Cellulose is absent in cell wall and is made of chitin and glucan (polysaccharide).\r\ng.   Filamentous except for unicellular yeast like Saccharomyces, Candida etc.\r\nh.   Grows as tubular, thread-like filamentous structures called Hyphae. Network of hyphae formed by fusion of hyphae (anastomosis) is called \r\n       Mycelium. Certain parallel hyphae grow into linear aggregations called Mycelial cords that resembles plant roots and are hence referred to as \r\n        Rhizomorphs.\r\n\r\n4. Plantae.\r\n\r\na.  Plantae includes all eukaryotic chlorophyll-containing organisms commonly called plants. A few members are partially  heterotrophic such as the \r\n      insectivorous plants or parasites.\r\n b. Bladderwort and Venus fly trap are examples of insectivorous plants and Cuscuta is a parasite.\r\n c.  The plant cells have an eukaryotic structure with prominent chloroplasts and cell wall mainly made of cellulose.\r\n d.  The lengths of the haploid and diploid phases, and whether these phases are free– living or dependent on others, vary among different groups in \r\n      plants. This phenomenon is called alternation of generation\r\n \r\n5. Animalia \r\n\r\na. This kingdom is characterised by heterotrophic eukaryotic organisms that are multicellular and their cells lack cell walls.\r\n\r\nb. They directly or indirectly depend on plants for food. They digest their food in an internal cavity and store food reserves as glycogen or fat. \r\n\r\nc. Their mode of nutrition is holozoic – by ingestion of food. They follow a definite growth pattern and grow into adults that have a definite shape \r\n    and  size. \r\nd. Higher forms show elaborate sensory and neuromotor mechanism.\r\n\r\ne. The sexual reproduction is by copulation of male and female followed by embryological development'),
('MONERA KINGDOM', 'KINGDOM MONERA:\r\n\r\nBased on the shape bacteria can be categorized as \r\n1. Cocci: Spherical shaped\r\n2. Bacilli: Rod shaped\r\n3. Vibrium: Comma-shaped\r\n4. Spirillum: spiral \r\n5. Spirochaetes: corkscrew shaped.\r\n\r\n6.  Includes bacteria that are ubiquitously present. \r\n7. They can exist as single cells (E.coli), in pairs (diplococci: S.pneumoniae, N.gonorrhoeae) , in chains (S.pyogenes) or clusters (S.aureus).\r\n\r\n8. Cell wall made of amino acids and polysaccharides.\r\n9. Internal compartmentalization is absent but has plasma membrane.\r\n10. Microscopic and cannot be seen with naked eye. \r\n11. No defined nucleus. Genetic material is present in the protoplasm as a dot. Nuclear membrane is absent.\r\n\r\n12. Membrane bound organelles are absent.\r\n13. Mitotic spindle is absent.\r\n\r\nBacteria move using a hair like structure called flagellum (pl: flagella). Flagella are cytoplasmic extensions made of flagellin protein that are intricately embedded in the cell membrane. They are about 12-30 nm in diameter and 5-16 µm in length. Based on flagella bacteria are categorized as 4 types:\r\n1. Atrichous: No flagellum  (Myxococcus xanthus)\r\n2. Monotrichous: Single flagellum at one end (V.cholerae)\r\n3. Amphitrichous: Two flagellum , one at each end (Alkaligens faecalis)\r\n4. Lophotrichous: Tuft of flagellum at one or both ends (Spirullum)\r\n5. Peritrichous: Numerous flagella all around the bacterium (S.typhi; E.coli)\r\n\r\nBacteria can obtain nutrition either by synthesizing their own food (Autotrophic) from inorganic sources (chemosynthetic: ) or from organic acids or carbon monoxide (photosynthetic : Cyanobacteria). Certain bacteria like Rhizobium have ability to fix atmospheric nitrogen into ammonia. \r\n\r\nBacteria can also obtain nutrition by depending on environment for energy. They are either parasitic (depends on a host for survival: S.typhi, M.tuberculosis) or saprophytic (derives energy by decomposing dead organic matter: E.coli). \r\n\r\nBacteria reproduce mainly by asexual mode of Binary fission and can exchange DNA through conjugation, transformation and transduction. \r\nBacteria are categorized as Archaebacteria and Eubacteria. \r\n\r\nArchaebacteria:\r\n\r\na. Recent studies propose Archae to be considered as distinct Kingdom.  \r\nb. They have extreme climatic or harsh climatic regions as their habitat. \r\nc.  They differ from other bacteria as they do not have polysaccharide amino-acid i.e. peptidoglycan cell wall. Hence, can thrive at harsh climates.\r\nd.  Thermophiles: survives at temperatures 20-70 degrees.  \r\ne.  Thermoacidophiles: Survives at low pH 2-3.  (Sulfolobus and Pyro Baculum)\r\nf.  Hyperthermophiles: Survives at temperatures 60-90 degrees. (Sulfolobus and Pyro Baculum)\r\ng.  Halophiles: Survives in highly salty regions. (Haloarchae)\r\nh.  Methanogens: Produces methane as byproduct in hypoxic environment. Found in the gut of ruminants and helps in biogas production in their \r\n     dung. \r\n\r\nEubacteria\r\n\r\nA rigid Peptidoglycan cell wall.\r\n\r\na. Cyanobacteria (blue-green algae) is the only photosynthetic autotrophic bacteria. Unicellular, colonial, filamentous bacteria inhabitants of \r\n     freshwater/marine water or terrestrial regions.\r\nb. The colonies of Cyanobacteria are enclosed by gelatinous sheath. Few Cyanobacteria, Nostoc and Anabaena  can fix atmospheric nitrogen in \r\n    Heterocysts. \r\nc.  Mycoplasma are the most primitive organisms. They are tiniest and can survive without oxygen. They are hetetrophic and are quite pathogenic \r\n     (causes PID and atypical pneumonia)\r\n \r\n\r\n'),
('Archaebacteria', 'a. Recent studies propose Archae to be considered as distinct Kingdom.  \r\nb. They have extreme climatic or harsh climatic regions as their habitat. \r\nc. They differ from other bacteria as they do not have polysaccharide amino-acid i.e. peptidoglycan cell wall. Hence, can thrive at harsh climates.\r\nd. Thermophiles: survives at temperatures 20-70 degrees.  \r\ne. Thermoacidophiles: Survives at low pH 2-3.  (Sulfolobus and Pyro Baculum)\r\nf. Hyperthermophiles: Survives at temperatures 60-90 degrees. (Sulfolobus and Pyro Baculum)\r\ng. Halophiles: Survives in highly salty regions. (Haloarchae)\r\nh. Methanogens: Produces methane as byproduct in hypoxic environment. Found in the gut of ruminants and helps in biogas production in their \r\n    dung. \r\n'),
('What is Archaebacteria ?', 'a. Recent studies propose Archae to be considered as distinct Kingdom.  \r\nb. They have extreme climatic or harsh climatic regions as their habitat. \r\nc. They differ from other bacteria as they do not have polysaccharide amino-acid i.e. peptidoglycan cell wall. Hence, can thrive at harsh climates.\r\nd. Thermophiles: survives at temperatures 20-70 degrees.  \r\ne. Thermoacidophiles: Survives at low pH 2-3.  (Sulfolobus and Pyro Baculum)\r\nf. Hyperthermophiles: Survives at temperatures 60-90 degrees. (Sulfolobus and Pyro Baculum)\r\ng. Halophiles: Survives in highly salty regions. (Haloarchae)\r\nh. Methanogens: Produces methane as byproduct in hypoxic environment. Found in the gut of ruminants and helps in biogas production in their \r\n    dung. \r\n'),
('Eubacteria', 'a. A rigid Peptidoglycan cell wall.\r\n\r\nb. Cyanobacteria (blue-green algae) is the only photosynthetic autotrophic bacteria. Unicellular, colonial, filamentous bacteria inhabitants of \r\n    freshwater/marine water or terrestrial regions. \r\n\r\nc. The colonies of Cyanobacteria are enclosed by gelatinous sheath. Few Cyanobacteria, Nostoc and Anabaena can fix atmospheric nitrogen in \r\n    heterocysts. \r\nd.  Mycoplasma are the most primitive organisms. They are tiniest and can survive without oxygen. They are heterotrophic and are quite pathogenic \r\n   (causes PID and atypical pneumonia)\r\n \r\n'),
('What is Eubacteria?', 'a. A rigid Peptidoglycan cell wall.\r\n\r\nb. Cyanobacteria (blue-green algae) is the only photosynthetic autotrophic bacteria. Unicellular, colonial, filamentous bacteria inhabitants of \r\n    freshwater/marine water or terrestrial regions. \r\n\r\nc. The colonies of Cyanobacteria are enclosed by gelatinous sheath. Few Cyanobacteria, Nostoc and Anabaena can fix atmospheric nitrogen in \r\n    heterocysts. \r\nd.  Mycoplasma are the most primitive organisms. They are tiniest and can survive without oxygen. They are heterotrophic and are quite pathogenic \r\n   (causes PID and atypical pneumonia)\r\n \r\n'),
('KINGDOM PROTISTA', 'a. Single celled Eukaryotes.\r\nb. Mostly aquatic with well-defined nucleus with histone DNA and membrane bound organelles.\r\nc. Few have cilia or flagella with 9+2 organization of microtubules having tubulin.  \r\nd. Reproduce both asexually through binary fission and sexually through cell fusion and zygote formation.\r\ne. They obtain energy through autotrophic holophytic mode i.e. vide photosynthesis in presence of light and heterotrophic holozoic mode i.e., vide \r\n    ingestion of inorganic material in absence of light.\r\n\r\nCategorized into following major categories:\r\n\r\n1. Chrysophytes:\r\n\r\na. Includes diatoms and desimeds (golden algae).\r\nb. Fresh water habitats\r\nc. Microscopic and floats on water bodies as plankton.\r\nd. Mostly autotrophic via photosynthesis.\r\ne. Cell wall of diatoms are embedded with silica and are overlapping thin shells like a soap box.\r\nf. Due to presence of silica in cell wall, the diatoms’ cell wall is nearly indestructible and hence, the same accumulates into Diatomaceous Earth that \r\n    is used in polishing, filtration of oils and syrups. \r\nh. Diatoms are the chief producers of marine bodies. \r\n    Examples: Bacillariophyceae, Fragilariopsis (diatoms) and Closterium (Desmids)  \r\n\r\n2. Dinoflagellates (Dinophyta):\r\n \r\na. Marine and photosynthetic \r\nb. Have different pigments and hence, appears in different colors. \r\nc. Di-flagellate with one longitudinal and one transverse flagella in between the wall plates. \r\nd.  Cell wall is rigid and has cellulose plates. \r\ne. Red dinoflagellates have rapid multiplication rates and thus may impart redness to tides. Toxins released by such organisms are fatal to marine \r\n    life. \r\n\r\n3. Euglenoids (Euglenozoa):\r\n \r\na. Freshwater organisms found in stagnant regions.\r\nb. Proteinaceous pellicle instead of cell wall. Hence, have high flexibility. \r\nc. Di-flagellate with one long and one short.\r\nd. Has pigments similar to those of plants.\r\ne. Autotrophic nutrition through photosynthesis in presence of sunlight (holophytic) but in absence of sunlight, they are heterotrophic by predating \r\n    on smaller organisms(saprophytic) or by ingesting food and digesting it (holozoic).  \r\n    Examples: Euglena, Phacus, Eutreptia.\r\n\r\n4. Slime molds:\r\n\r\na. Damp habitats\r\nb. Heterotrophic nutrition through saprophytic mode. Hence, helps in decomposition and decay. \r\nc.  Amoeba like cells. \r\nd. They aggregate to form Plasmodia under favourable conditions. Plasmodium contains many nuclei without cell membrane. The plasmodia can \r\n  grow and stretch to large areas engulfing bacteria. Protoplasm of plasmodia can move @ 1.35 mm per second. \r\ne. Under unfavourable conditions, the plasmodia will form fruiting bodies called Sporangia and these have rigid cell walls that can enable the  \r\n   plasmodia to survive in adverse conditions. \r\nf. Spores, dispersed through air, can hatch to independent amoeba like unicellular slime molds. \r\n    Examples: Physarum polycephalum, Dictyostelium discoidem. \r\n\r\n\r\n5. Protozoans (Protozoa):\r\n \r\na. Heterotrophs and are either predatory or parasitic in nature. \r\nb. Believed to share phyletic relation with animals.\r\nc. Grouped into four major groups\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n'),
('Explain the \"PROTESTA\" KINGDOM ', 'a. Single celled Eukaryotes.\r\nb. Mostly aquatic with well-defined nucleus with histone DNA and membrane bound organelles.\r\nc. Few have cilia or flagella with 9+2 organization of microtubules having tubulin.  \r\nd. Reproduce both asexually through binary fission and sexually through cell fusion and zygote formation.\r\ne. They obtain energy through autotrophic holophytic mode i.e. vide photosynthesis in presence of light and heterotrophic holozoic mode i.e., vide \r\n    ingestion of inorganic material in absence of light.\r\n\r\nCategorized into following major categories:\r\n\r\n1. Chrysophytes:\r\n\r\na. Includes diatoms and desimeds (golden algae).\r\nb. Fresh water habitats\r\nc. Microscopic and floats on water bodies as plankton.\r\nd. Mostly autotrophic via photosynthesis.\r\ne. Cell wall of diatoms are embedded with silica and are overlapping thin shells like a soap box.\r\nf. Due to presence of silica in cell wall, the diatoms’ cell wall is nearly indestructible and hence, the same accumulates into Diatomaceous Earth that \r\n    is used in polishing, filtration of oils and syrups. \r\nh. Diatoms are the chief producers of marine bodies. \r\n    Examples: Bacillariophyceae, Fragilariopsis (diatoms) and Closterium (Desmids)  \r\n\r\n2. Dinoflagellates (Dinophyta):\r\n \r\na. Marine and photosynthetic \r\nb. Have different pigments and hence, appears in different colors. \r\nc. Di-flagellate with one longitudinal and one transverse flagella in between the wall plates. \r\nd.  Cell wall is rigid and has cellulose plates. \r\ne. Red dinoflagellates have rapid multiplication rates and thus may impart redness to tides. Toxins released by such organisms are fatal to marine \r\n    life. \r\n\r\n3. Euglenoids (Euglenozoa):\r\n \r\na. Freshwater organisms found in stagnant regions.\r\nb. Proteinaceous pellicle instead of cell wall. Hence, have high flexibility. \r\nc. Di-flagellate with one long and one short.\r\nd. Has pigments similar to those of plants.\r\ne. Autotrophic nutrition through photosynthesis in presence of sunlight (holophytic) but in absence of sunlight, they are heterotrophic by predating \r\n    on smaller organisms(saprophytic) or by ingesting food and digesting it (holozoic).  \r\n    Examples: Euglena, Phacus, Eutreptia.\r\n\r\n4. Slime molds:\r\n\r\na. Damp habitats\r\nb. Heterotrophic nutrition through saprophytic mode. Hence, helps in decomposition and decay. \r\nc.  Amoeba like cells. \r\nd. They aggregate to form Plasmodia under favourable conditions. Plasmodium contains many nuclei without cell membrane. The plasmodia can \r\n  grow and stretch to large areas engulfing bacteria. Protoplasm of plasmodia can move @ 1.35 mm per second. \r\ne. Under unfavourable conditions, the plasmodia will form fruiting bodies called Sporangia and these have rigid cell walls that can enable the  \r\n   plasmodia to survive in adverse conditions. \r\nf. Spores, dispersed through air, can hatch to independent amoeba like unicellular slime molds. \r\n    Examples: Physarum polycephalum, Dictyostelium discoidem. \r\n\r\n\r\n5. Protozoans (Protozoa):\r\n \r\na. Heterotrophs and are either predatory or parasitic in nature. \r\nb. Believed to share phyletic relation with animals.\r\nc. Grouped into four major groups\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n'),
('KINGDOM FUNGI ', '1. Heterotrophic organisms depending on either dead substrates (Saprophytic) or on plants and animals (parasitic) with rich diversity in morphology \r\n    and habitat.\r\n2. Few fungi live in association with algae as Lichens and with roots of plants as Mycorrhiza through symbiotic relation. \r\n3. They are cosmopolitan and present in air, water, soil, animals and plants and mostly found at damp places. \r\n4. Few fungi are pathogenic and infects animals, plants etc. \r\n5.Principal decomposers in ecological systems. \r\n6. Cellulose is absent in cell wall and is made of chitin and glucan (polysaccharide).\r\n7. Filamentous except for unicellular yeast like Saccharomyces, Candida etc.\r\n8. Grows as tubular, thread-like filamentous structures called Hyphae. Network of hyphae formed by fusion of hyphae (anastomosis) is called \r\n      Mycelium. Certain parallel hyphae grow into linear aggregations called Mycelial cords that resembles plant roots and are hence referred to as \r\n      Rhizomorphs.\r\n10.  Few Hyphae has multi-nucleated cytoplasm, and such hyphae are called Coenocytic Hyphae. Other Hyphae has septa between the nuclei.\r\n\r\n11. Two morphological stages: Vegetative and reproductive.\r\n\r\nA.   Growth is at tip of hyphae (Spitzenkorper) and reproduction is through following modes:\r\n1. Vegetative reproduction: By fission or budding (Yeast) or mycelial fragmentation \r\n2. Asexual reproduction: By spores called conidia or zoospores or sporangiospores \r\n3. Sexual reproduction: by spores, oospores or ascospores or basidiospores, formed through sexual cycle including meiosis. Spores are produced by \r\n   fruiting bodies like Ascocarp, Basidiocarp etc.\r\n \r\n4. Sporangiophore: Reproductive hyphae\r\n5. Sporangium: Protective sac like structure at the end of sporangiophore.\r\n\r\n6. Spore: Cells that are capable of germinating into new mycelia/hyphae\r\n7. Sporogenesis: Process of formation of spores\r\n8.  Mitotic division of haploid parent cells = Asexual spores\r\n9.  Fusion of protoplasm, dikaryotic stage, karyogamy and meiosis results in sexual spores called Zygospores.\r\n \r\nB. Process of Sexual reproduction in fungi:\r\n \r\n1. Occurs between two compatible mating types either homothallic (in same mycelia) or heterothallic (different but compatible mycelia) Occurs in \r\n    three stages. \r\n2. Compatible haploid hyphae fuse together = Anastomosis. The  protoplasm of the hyphae fuse together = Plasmogamy.\r\n3.  In certain classes of fungi, the nuclei fuse immediately (karyogamy) after anastomosis or plasmogamy to form a diploid cell. However, in fungi \r\n       like Ascomycetes and Basidiomycetes the nuclei do not fuse immediately but exist in dikaryophase as dikaryon i.e., two nuclei from two \r\n     protoplasm, cohabit but does not fuse.  Later karyogamy occurs resulting in diploid cells. \r\n4. Meiosis of diploid cells to form haploid spores occurs in the fruiting body of the fungi (Ascospores/Basidiospores).\r\n \r\n5. These spores can be dispersed and can germinate into new mycelium.\r\n \r\n\r\n C. Based on the mode of spore formation, mycelium morphology and fruiting bodies fungi are classified into different classes :\r\n\r\nI.  Phycomycetes\r\n\r\n1. Members of phycomycetes are found in aquatic habitats and on decaying wood in moist and damp places or as obligate parasites on plants. The \r\n   mycelium is aseptate and coenocytic. \r\n2. Asexual reproduction takes place by zoospores (motile) or by aplanospores (non-motile). \r\n3. These spores are endogenously produced in sporangium. A zygospore is formed by fusion of two gametes.\r\n4. These gametes are similar in morphology (isogamous) or dissimilar (anisogamous or oogamous). Some common examples are Mucor (Rhizopus \r\n     (the bread mold mentioned earlier) and Albugo.\r\n\r\nII. Ascomycetes:\r\n\r\n1. Commonly known as sac-fungi, the as comycetes are mostly multicellular, e.g., Penicillium, or rarely unicellular, e.g., yeast (Saccharomyces). \r\n      They are saprophytic, decomposers, parasitic or coprophilous (growing on dung). \r\n2.   Mycelium is branched and septate. \r\n3. The asexual spores are conidia produced exogenously on the special mycelium called conidiophores. Conidia on germination produce mycelium. \r\n      Sexual spores are called ascospores which are produced endogenously in sac like asci (singular ascus). \r\n4. These asci are arranged in different types of fruiting bodies called ascocarps. Some examples are Aspergillus (Figure 2.5b), Claviceps and \r\n   Neurospora.\r\n5.  Neurospora is used extensively in biochemical and genetic work. \r\n6.  Many members like morels and truffles are edible and are considered delicacies.\r\n\r\nIII.  Basidiomycetes\r\n\r\n1. Commonly known forms of basidiomycetes are mushrooms, bracket fungi or puffballs. They grow in soil, on logs and tree stumps and in living \r\n     plant bodies as parasites, e.g., rusts and smuts.\r\n2.  The mycelium is branched and septate. The asexual spores are generally not found, but vegetative reproduction by fragmentation is common.\r\n3.  The sex organs are absent, but plasmogamy is brought about by fusion of two vegetative or somatic cells of different strains or genotypes.\r\n4.  The resultant structure is dikaryotic which ultimately gives rise to basidium. Karyogamy and meiosis take place in the basidium producing four \r\n        basidiospores. \r\n5. The basidiospores are exogenously produced on the basidium (pl.: basidia). \r\n6.  The basidia are arranged in fruiting bodies called basidiocarps. Some common members are Agaricus (mushroom) (Figure 2.5c), Ustilago (smut).\r\n\r\nIV.  Deuteromycetes:\r\n\r\n1. Commonly known as imperfect fungi because only the asexual or vegetative phases of these fungi are known. When the sexual forms of these \r\n     fungi were discovered they were moved into classes they rightly belong to.\r\n2.  It is also possible that the asexual and vegetative stage have been given one name (and placed under deuteromycetes) and the sexual stage \r\n      another (and placed under another class). Later when the linkages were established. \r\n3.   The deuteromycetes reproduce only by asexual spores known as conidia. The mycelium is septate and branched. Some members are saprophytes \r\n      or parasites while a large number of them are decomposers of litter and help in mineral cycling. \r\n4.  Some examples are Alternaria, Colletotrichum and Trichoderma.\r\n\r\n'),
('Explain the  \"FUNGI\" KINGDOM.', '1. Heterotrophic organisms depending on either dead substrates (Saprophytic) or on plants and animals (parasitic) with rich diversity in morphology \r\n    and habitat.\r\n2. Few fungi live in association with algae as Lichens and with roots of plants as Mycorrhiza through symbiotic relation. \r\n3. They are cosmopolitan and present in air, water, soil, animals and plants and mostly found at damp places. \r\n4. Few fungi are pathogenic and infects animals, plants etc. \r\n5.Principal decomposers in ecological systems. \r\n6. Cellulose is absent in cell wall and is made of chitin and glucan (polysaccharide).\r\n7. Filamentous except for unicellular yeast like Saccharomyces, Candida etc.\r\n8. Grows as tubular, thread-like filamentous structures called Hyphae. Network of hyphae formed by fusion of hyphae (anastomosis) is called \r\n      Mycelium. Certain parallel hyphae grow into linear aggregations called Mycelial cords that resembles plant roots and are hence referred to as \r\n      Rhizomorphs.\r\n10.  Few Hyphae has multi-nucleated cytoplasm, and such hyphae are called Coenocytic Hyphae. Other Hyphae has septa between the nuclei.\r\n\r\n11. Two morphological stages: Vegetative and reproductive.\r\n\r\nA.   Growth is at tip of hyphae (Spitzenkorper) and reproduction is through following modes:\r\n1. Vegetative reproduction: By fission or budding (Yeast) or mycelial fragmentation \r\n2. Asexual reproduction: By spores called conidia or zoospores or sporangiospores \r\n3. Sexual reproduction: by spores, oospores or ascospores or basidiospores, formed through sexual cycle including meiosis. Spores are produced by \r\n   fruiting bodies like Ascocarp, Basidiocarp etc.\r\n \r\n4. Sporangiophore: Reproductive hyphae\r\n5. Sporangium: Protective sac like structure at the end of sporangiophore.\r\n\r\n6. Spore: Cells that are capable of germinating into new mycelia/hyphae\r\n7. Sporogenesis: Process of formation of spores\r\n8.  Mitot